Republican Party's strategy against Obama's re-election
Republican leaders justified their policies by the need to combat voter fraud.
However, the Brennan Center calls such a fraud a myth, saying that voter fraud is less common in the U.S. than the number of people who die after a lightning strike.
In fact, Republican attorneys have recorded only 300 cases of voter fraud in the U.S. over the past decade.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike Canada, the United States is responsible for the organization of federal elections.
And in this spirit, most U.S. governments have enacted new laws since 2009 that make it difficult to vote or register.
This phenomenon saw a surge after the November 2010 election, during which 675 new Republican representatives were added in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills restricting voting rights in 41 states were submitted in 2011 alone.
New election laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws limit the period for elections in advance, invalidate the right to register on the electoral roll on the day of the elections and deprive citizens with a criminal record of their right to vote.
Before the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID.
The first state to implement this requirement was Indiana.
The constitutionality of Indian law was confirmed by the U.S. Supreme Court in 2008.
The Republican authorities were in a hurry to extend this procedure to other states.
Over the past two years, they have supported such bills in 34 states to force voters to present photo IDs.
It should be noted that unlike Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity card, such as a health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, i.e., 21 million people of voting age, do not have a photo ID issued by their state’s government office.
In addition, about five million new voters did not have such an identity card in 2012.
In addition, obtaining the required identity card often costs more than a hundred dollars.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect mainly young people, members of minorities and people with low incomes.
Twenty-five percent of African-Americans, 15 percent of people with incomes below $35,000, 18 percent of citizens over 65, and 20 percent of voters between the ages of 18 and 29 do not have the required photo ID.
And that's not all.
Students who are known as voters for their fondness for democratic candidates are not allowed to use their photo ID issued by their school in several states.
On the other hand, the same States allow members of hunting or fishing clubs who prefer Republican candidates to use the cards issued by those clubs in elections.
Until 2004, no state required proof of citizenship for elections.
Arizona introduced the first such requirement.
Since 2011, about 12 states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the number of votes from the Hispanic minority.
It should be noted that two out of three Hispanics prefer the Democratic Party.
In 2011, Republican lawmakers backed legislation in eight states that scrapped voter registration on election day.
In addition, they have restricted the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to voters who wish to register.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, during the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns helped to register some 10 million people.
However, the measures taken after 2009 caused a 17% decrease in the number of new voters in 2010 compared to 2006.
In five other states, Republican lawmakers have passed laws aimed at shortening the period for early elections.
For example, during the 2008 general election in Florida, African-Americans made up 33% of voters who voted in advance, even though African-American voters in that state were only 13%.
It was the same with the Hispanics.
They made up only 11% of all voters, but 24% of the citizens voting in advance.
On the other hand, whites, who represented 76% of all voters, accounted for only 46% of voters who voted in advance.
Of course, democratic legislators and their supporters have strongly opposed the adoption of laws restricting voter registration.
Democratic governors have vetoed several bills.
In order to suspend the validity of the most controversial laws, even the Attorney General of the United States intervened.
The damage was partially reduced.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states have passed laws requiring the submission of a photo ID card.
However, the newly introduced rules will indisputably hinder the exercise of the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics speak above all about the bias of the laws passed and consider them to be an obvious attempt to influence the results of the 2012 elections in key states.
A 2011 report by the Brennan Center shows that the states where these laws were passed represent 171 of the 270 votes in the electorate needed to win the presidential election.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes at the level of the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential election.
But one thing is certain today: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
Detection of prostate cancer: to undergo an examination or not?
