Higgs boson investigated
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson caused a legitimate stir last summer.
There is an opinion that this boson is involved in the mechanism that is responsible for all the matter in the universe.
And then there's the last particle whose existence is predicted by a standard model - our best or "least bad" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - that has not yet been empirically observed.
However, there is still no 100% certainty among physicists that it is a Higgs boson.
There is no doubt that we have a completely new particle at our disposal that is very similar to the Higgs boson, as predicted by the standard model.
The new data released this week during the great physical congress in Kyoto rather confirm it, but all the data is still missing so that we can be absolutely sure.
However, let's assume that this is a Higgs boson, since the risk of error appears to be small, and let's look at what it is.
There is an indisputable law in this world according to which two things cannot occur at the same time in the same place.
This rule can not be circumvented - and do not try to do it too hard, otherwise you will hurt yourself.
Although particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that a similar law applies to it: Pauli's exclusion principle, according to which two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" roughly creates some of their properties.
It also divides physical particles into two categories.
On the one hand, we find orderly citizens, or fermions, obediently adhering to the Pauli principle.
And at the other end there are barefoot, vile anarchists who don't value anything at all - certainly not this principle, which means they can be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are further divided into two groups according to the device (by the way absolutely amazing), which is The Particle Adventure, in Berkeley laboratories: the mesons that we leave unnoticed here, and the "force particles" with which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs boson is probably in some way related.
However, it must be said that these bosons are not as exotic animals as one might think.
If you read this article, it is thanks to a boson with an unusual banality: a photon, or "particle of light", which is the "carrier" of electromagnetic force.
When a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "interrupts" the electromagnetic field at that particular location, much like a pebble thrown into a pond.
From this "interference" arises an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.) and this wave is nothing but a photon - and therefore one of the bosons, the "bearers of force".
A more stable field
So is the Higgs boson, except that you have to "interrupt" another field, the Higgs field, in order for this boson to appear.
This Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; very high energy values must be reached for its excitation, similar to the frozen level of a pond, where only a very large boulder is present.
For this reason, it is necessary to use such a huge accelerator part as the accelerator in the CERN laboratory - a large hadron accelerator with reciprocal bundles is a circle with a circumference of 27 km! - in order to develop such energy.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again useful to clarify the relationship between the Higgs and matter.
Neither all particles nor all materials react with the electromagnetic field.
Some, such as magnets, do so, but others do not - a piece of paper, for example, will never keep on the refrigerator by itself.
Similarly, not all particles react with the Higgs field: those that do have a certain mass, while others (like a photon, let's look at it) don't.
And Mrs. Nováková asks what all this research is about, what will it "bring us"?
From a scientific point of view, this is a confirmation of the validity of the Standard Model (SM), which allows physicists to examine any discrepancy between the observations and the predictions of SM.
In addition, many physicists literally wish to be able to find them, because the slightest difference could open up the space of "new physics" and fix some gaps in the model.
It should be noted that the model still has huge flaws, does not bring any clarification of gravity (ooh!) or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the universe's mass (again, ooh!).
However, CERN has so far failed to detect such discrepancies.
Testimonials
The reactions of these researches in the everyday life of Mr. and Mrs. Novak can only be very difficult to predict, but it would be a mistake to believe that there will be none.
At the very beginning of the 1960s, the laser pioneers in Bell Labs had no idea of the revolution their work would spark.
They assumed scientific use, but nothing else.
Physicist Willard Boyle - who worked at Bell Labs where the laser was invented in 1960, and who created the first permanent laser beam (previous beams were pulsed) in 1962, I have already said this - the laser was initially considered such a "laboratory toy".
Just imagine...
In addition, the application can also result from all the tools that surround the research.
For example, the same Willard Boyle created a small light sensor in 1969 during his work on optics.
This sensor, although not originally planned by Boyle, now serves as the "eye" of all digital cameras in the world and won him the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
Of course, this does not mean that activities around the LHC necessarily have to change our lives, but it does mean that you really never know...
