The bitcoin exchange rate first reached a maximum of $30 ($23) in June 2011, five months later it fell to $2, today it is hovering around $10 (a list of exchange rates is available on bitcoincharts.com).
Compared to the world exchange for real money or financial products, this is nothing impressive.
And yet, the European Central Bank (ECB) is interested in this fact in its report on virtual finance, which was published in October.
Bitcoin has been described as “the most successful virtual money,” “competing the dollar and the euro,” and “the equivalent of regular money.”
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual money in that it is like the “credits” used to advance a video game that a person acquires through a game or that he or she can purchase (and sometimes exchange back).
The social network Facebook has also developed a similar system.
Each month, however, the central authority checks and processes individual communications.
In the case of Bitcoin, all nodes of the network are depositaries of books of current accounts, controllers, money issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users is actually between two e-mail addresses.
However, the user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
The file of information related to this transaction is electronically signed by a double-key encryption system.
Thus, the network can verify the legitimacy of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the exchanged bitcoins exist in a public ledger of current accounts, which is distributed throughout the network.
The key phase is to write this new transaction into this book.
It takes place by solving a mathematical problem assigned to computers, the solver of which, a temporary central banker, will have the right to write this additional line.
This is a phase of file slicing; i.e., transforming a huge file into a shorter and unique digital footprint.
Computers "take over" this new transaction and add a number to it, only then "cut" the whole.
The goal is to find a number that provides a specific imprint (a lot of zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, other nodes will easily check its correctness.
The transaction is then indestructibly displayed connected to the chain of all other transactions; any modification would change the imprint.
If the user wanted to pay twice the same money very quickly in a row (within ten minutes), the network will confirm only one of the two transactions - the other will be abandoned, because each of them has a different imprint.
The computer that solves the challenge wins 50 bitcoins.
In order to avoid inflation, this reward is divided regularly by two, probably by the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is thus limited to 21 million, but they can be divided up to a hundred millionth, so there is room for margin.
The difficulty of the given task also increases with the increasing level of calculation.
The network has already experienced its ups and downs.
Websites that provide services for Bitcoin have been attacked and stored bitcoins have been stolen.
“The loophole used does not relate to the protocol itself,” assures Pierre Noizat, who founded Paymium, a real-money payment company that uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also controls the possibility of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But this problem also applies to cash.
Notable players such as Wikipedia reject gifts of this nature.
Others, like the WordPress blog platform, accept them.
Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron from the Weizmann Institute in Israel recently analyzed a book of current accounts and showed that almost 80% of bitcoins do not circulate.
In November, "huge discounts" were launched.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” says Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, a bitcoin-to-gold conversion company.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a pedagogical book on this money, has great confidence in the potential of this technology as a transactional network.
Its system, Paytunia, is the equivalent of a credit card (with real money) or contactless mobile payment, but it uses a Bitcoin system to authenticate transactions that are thus cheaper.
In addition, the carrier manages its identity and can remain anonymous.
The system is easy to set up for merchants where there is no need to install new terminals or software.
It is enough to give an address that can be "photographed and recognized" by the phone, says Pierre Noizat, who assures that he already has thousands of users.
There is a general movement to challenge hierarchical systems and move to more horizontal systems.
“Bitcoin will take some time to assert itself, but 2013 could be a decisive year,” he predicts.
In addition, the ECB’s report foresees a reassessment of the various risks that are now considered to be increased if this type of money is successful.
We left Afghanistan.
What's next?
French troops have left their area of responsibility in Afghanistan (Kapisa and Surobi).
NATO and U.S. forces are expected to follow by the end of 2014.
It is time for the Afghan army to take control of its territory and for the Afghans to choose their own future and not expect everything from us.
The greatest damage was done to the people in the Afghan countryside, whom we punished because we considered them terrorists.
And so did we, after all, we lost 88 soldiers killed, and what about all the injuries and mutilations.
The Taliban are made up of foreign extremists, former leaders who fled to Pakistan, but they are often peasants who reject the presence of foreign armies as in Soviet times.
They just want to defend their ancient and archaic traditions, even if they are joined by jihadists, Pakistanis, Arabs, Uzbeks, Tajiks.
They are now experiencing tolerance and frequent help from local insurgents, but if Western forces withdraw, their support will decline.
The departure of the French troops from the base of Nijrab, which I observed from the tops of the mountains planted with almonds thanks to French loans, took place in an orderly manner.
Convoys of trucks and armored vehicles arrived in Kabul without being attacked by helicopters.
By the end of 2014, the Taliban will no longer be active in Kabul.
Since their unstoppable advance between 1994 and 1996, conditions have changed considerably.
Kabul was empty at the time, and the land was in blood and fire as a result of fighting between various resistance groups.
Their taking control of the country was then considered a kind of liberation, a return to security.
The Afghans paid a price for the obscurity of these villagers, who were completely dominated by the Al-Qaeda organization, but their situation has not improved in our time.
The former Mujahideen, the Afghan government and the current Taliban are all in agreement in their efforts to keep women in a subordinate position.
The main dignitaries from the war against the Soviet troops returned to power in 2001.
They became traffickers, seized state-owned land that they sold as construction land to refugees from Iran and Pakistan, and took advantage of huge U.S. contracts for subcontractors.
They had discredited themselves; most of them had never even been in combat.
From what I've heard in the campaigns, people want a government that's not made up of thieves.
Many young people want to leave the way those who have been able to take advantage of America’s generosity will: capital flight is considerable.
Young people are tired of war and its associated ideologies.
During their exile in Iran or Pakistan, they came to know the modern world, and its benefits caught their attention.
About 65% of the population is under the age of 25; Kabul is currently home to 5 million people, a fifth of the total population.
In the cities, public schools are full, girls and boys go there.
These young people will have to be provided with work, they no longer want to return to the obscurity of the former parties or to the corruption of some representatives.
Everyone, including the armed opposition, likes mobile phones; they watch TV and Turkish TV shows that show the modern world everywhere.
The army is already present.
Will the authorities that head it be considered legitimate?
The former commanders of the struggle against the Soviet army are already restoring provincial militias that will be beyond the control of the central power.
Afghanistan, a mountainous country with a strong local identity influence, should enjoy a degree of decentralization modeled after Western states, but the US wanted to turn it into a centralized state with a strong presidential influence, so the post of prime minister, which had existed since the adoption of the constitution in 1964, was abolished.
President Karzai does not want foreign control, especially on the occasion of the elections scheduled for April 2014.
However, his country has been heavily dependent on foreign aid since the 1950s and earlier.
No industry has been restored, no dam is functioning, no major irrigation system has been repaired.
Everything is imported; nothing is produced except fruit and vegetables.
Preference is given to private initiative.
In a country destroyed by three decades of war, government control of infrastructure would be necessary.
Rumor has it that Afghanistan has vast mineral wealth.
And this only fueled the feeling that the Western states were there only to seize it.
Without energy to process iron ore or copper on site and without the means to transport raw materials across the mountains, no mining can take place.
The Chinese have almost left the Mes Aynak copper mine, leaving international archaeological teams (supported by the World Bank) the opportunity to explore the vast Buddhist site in order to retain the role of the most important employer in the entire province.
One day, it will also be necessary for Afghanistan and Pakistan, on which a large part of imports and exports depend, to restore normal relations.
The withdrawal of French combat troops was completed on 20 November.
The new cooperation agreement envisages the continuation of common types of assistance: girls' and boys' lyceums, French departments at universities, the French Institute, cooperation in the military, legal, medical and agricultural fields, support for the archaeological delegation.
Since 2009, the "winning heart and soul" initiative has been working on the difficult task of coordinating aid and military activities, within which the "civil-military steps" service of the Ministry of Defense (Cemic) operated, which was abolished in 2012, but achieved a number of successes in the field of common interest thanks to a small number of French agricultural NGOs.
These works, involving a large number of local workers, helped to quell the uprising: irrigation, wells, drinking water, afforestation, fruit trees, soil protection and the expansion of arable land.
What memory will we leave behind after <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>2 billion in military spending?
A much more modest budget would contribute to the improvement of local living conditions, which are very demanding in these valleys, which are often at altitudes above 2 000 m.
The Embassy has received dozens of written requests for small-scale agricultural assistance from local communities in the province of Kapisa.
In order to free these farmers from the revolts led by foreign groups, they wish, in their own words, to obtain a small amount of civil aid for their benefit, which would be properly controlled and would affect them directly.
Difficult work on the Egyptian constitution
President Mohamed Morsi is playing another game of poker.
While Egypt remains the most divided in its history due to the proclamation of a constitution that temporarily grants him unlimited powers, he decided to play vabank.
On Wednesday, he announced, regardless of the opinion of all the others, that the Constitutional Assembly would approve the final text the next day.
Less than a week ago, the head of state gave this assembly another two months to complete the necessary work.
For almost two years, Egypt has been using a provisional text, which has been amended many times, which weakens the country's constitutional stability and leads to legal speculation.
This new initiative only further strengthened the country's division.
From the point of view of the opposition, the president persists in his "autocratic delirium", continues to "violate his word" and "stomp the law".
However, his supporters say it is a means of dealing with the constitutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and speeding up the transitional process.
A referendum will be held in two weeks.
This is a very short period of time that will force the Brotherhood to withdraw from the intention of the text to the Egyptians to clarify the article after the article.
It is also a way for the president to regain national and democratic legitimacy while the whole country is in the throes of protests.
As he confirmed in an interview with the American weekly Time, Mohamed Morsi seems to be convinced that the Egyptians will vote in favor.
Especially because this hastily organised vote puts the Egyptian people before an ultimatum: 'Either you approve my text, or I will retain unlimited powers', which should otherwise end when the new constitution is approved.
And in this particular atmosphere yesterday, 85 deputies of the aforementioned constituent assembly with a large majority of Islamists approved the text.
Most of the Liberals were absent from the vote.
In mid-November, shortly before the proclamation of the Constitution, they slammed the door, saying that they had no opportunity to assert their views.
Human rights defenders, civil society or members of religious minorities imitated their step.
In order to achieve a quorum, 11 substitutes were hurriedly added yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising, then, that articles of the Constitution were often voted unanimously.
Commentators further paused to note that one of the few disputes that day revolved around... hours of prayer, when some committee members held the view that the meeting room hours were not set correctly.
The text, which was voted on last night, consists of 234 articles.
The subject of general attention, Article 2, remains ultimately consistent with the 1971 version of the Constitution and states that "the principles of Sharia law are the main source of law".
The Salafist parties, for whom the introduction of Islamic law is one of the fundamental requirements, hoped to replace the term "principles" with the term "rules", which would allow for stricter enforcement.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been corrected is a sign of their goodwill and respect for other parts of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrisy," the liberals object, who see it as a rhetorical problem.
Islamization of the Constitution is carried out through other articles.
They focus in particular on Article 220, which entrusts al-Azhar University with an advisory role, in particular on issues of checking the conformity of laws with Sharia law.
According to Egypt expert Sophie Pommier, this is disturbing because “persons called to expression are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
The beginnings of theocracy can be seen in this.”
The liberals’ fears are further fuelled by the fact that the next university rector should be less moderate than the current one.
“So far, there has been no concrete religious effect.
With this constitution, Egypt remains a civil state.
Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not ulama, but university workers, many of them graduated from French schools,” said Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a paper on the constitutional transition in Egypt.
However, they agree that "there may be contradictions as to the interpretation of Article 220, because the terms used therein belong to the religious vocabulary.
There is, in particular, a reference to "fiqh" [Islamic legal science, note ed.].
And in the future, the question may arise as to the extent to which civil judges are competent to comment on this.”
In addition to religious sites, the text approved yesterday has been heavily criticized for the expanded powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood insists that there has been a significant restriction on them compared to the former regime.
Another controversial point: the powers entrusted to the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the representatives of the army, the verification of the defense budget will not be carried out by the parliament, but by the National Defense Council.
Furthermore, civil proceedings in military courts will not be prohibited, as demanded by the association for the protection of human rights.
These associations speak of their doubts in the context of the text which they claim is directed against freedom.
The crime of blasphemy is maintained and insult continues to be prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, in particular for the press.
Moreover, no article deals with the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture referred to in Article 36.
This word was not mentioned in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president was scheduled to make a televised speech last night, demonstrations are scheduled for this afternoon.
The supporters of the head of state will then manifest on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists are waiting for holy places, the navel of the world and the sea from a saturated solution of salt
The Promised Land combines the grandeur of biblical truths, modern comfort, and the inviolability of nature.
AaF has identified the five most important reasons why you should visit Israel.
Worshiping the Holy Places
Visit the Jordan River, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that God’s mercy will descend on all who enter this “bath”.
And Galilee - the place of Jesus' miracles: turning water into wine at a wedding, walking on water, calming the storm and filling the nets.
Here, too, Jesus appeared to his disciples after the resurrection.
But the most holy places are in Jerusalem.
Here believers will walk the Path of Pain, or the Way of the Cross of Jesus (Latin: Via Dolorosa).
It begins at the fortress of Antonia - Pretoria - where the trial took place, passes through the streets of the Old Town and leads to the Temple of the Holy Sepulchre on Mount Golgotha - to the place of the crucifixion, to the stone of the anointing and the place where Jesus was buried.
Here is the symbolic Christian navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of mankind.
And the monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem was built on the place where, according to Christian legend, a tree grew, from which they made a cross for Jesus’ crucifixion.
Jerusalem is also home to the holiest site for Jews - the Wailing Wall, the rest of the temple that was destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
According to tradition, people of different faiths leave notes with wishes, which are then fulfilled.
Make your way through the vertical
The ruins of the fortress of Masada remained a secret hiding place from the enemy, which Herod the Great built in 25 BC for his family.
The ruin is located on cliffs in the mountains at an altitude of 450 m above sea level.
Only those who are engaged in mountaineering can get to it by their own forces.
The others will be taken to this historic mountain by a cable car.
And in the north of the country, at an altitude of 1600-2040 m, there is the famous Hermon ski resort, which experiences a huge influx of tourists in the winter months.
This ski paradise is served by a shuttle bus from the foot of the hill.
The total length of the mountain slopes is 45 km.
According to an ancient legend, pagan gods supposedly lived on the top of the mountain.
Visit the unique museums
There are about 300 museums in the country.
You won’t be able to visit all of them in one trip.
But at least five of them, the most interesting, are definitely worth a visit.
Among them is the Museum of Israel, which is located near the Knesset (parliament).
It houses ancient Qumran manuscripts, or Dead Sea Scrolls, found in the caves of the Judean Desert, as well as some 500,000 archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Tel Aviv Museum of Art is also worth a visit.
His paintings are widely represented by Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall, Picasso.
In Akkon, you can visit the Al Basha Spa Museum, which presents visitors with several rooms of ancient Turkish baths with figurines of bath users and spa nurses from that time.
In Caesarea it is worth visiting the unique private museum of Ralli, where you can admire the statues of Dal<0xC3><0xAD> and Rodin.
There are no guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free and gifts are strictly refused.
The fifth museum, the Yad Vashem Museum in Tel Aviv, tells the story of one of the most dramatic pages in history.
The most tragic part of the museum - the Children's Memorial - was built in memory of 1.5 million children who were murdered in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You walk in - and you find yourself in total darkness.
The stars are glittering.
And these are the names of the Jewish children, and the names of the countries in which they perished.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Improve your health
Israel’s three main spas are located on the Mediterranean, Red and Dead Sea coasts.
Each of them offers swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
It is interesting that in the Red Sea you can swim even in the winter months, because the water temperature in it does not fall below 21 degrees Celsius and the air warms up to 23 degrees.
The Dead Sea is even warmer, and people bathe in it all year round.
The Dead Sea, by the way, is the most peculiar sea in the world, located at the lowest land point on the planet - at 417 m below sea level.
The azure water in it is a saturated saline solution that easily keeps even people who can not swim on the surface.
The surrounding countryside is unrealistically beautiful.
Come here to undergo treatment using salt water - brine, and healing mud, which can treat health problems with dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes, to cure your swollen nerves.
Touch the mysterious ancient past
It is protected by the ancient part of Tel Aviv - the town of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
Through them passed the famous sea route connecting Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
References to this city are found in the oldest Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, this is the place where Noah built his ark and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with which they lived a long and happy life together.
Tourists really love wandering the narrow streets, named after the signs of the zodiac.
It is said that if you cling to the walls in the alley of "your" sign, your luck will be favorably inclined.
In Jaffa, you may meet newlyweds who come here from all over Israel and even from other countries to be photographed.
And in Caesarea - in the city of King Herod - you can take a walk through the Roman theater and "conquer" the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the capital of Judea and the seat of Roman procurators, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully reconstructed theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Tourists, a word
If you are going to Israel, you do not need to worry about your imperfect English: about 30% of the population speaks Russian in this country.
It is better to take money with you on the trip not in euros, but in dollars, which you can easily exchange for shekels (now 1 dollar is about 3.8 shekels).
The city's main transportation is buses, but there is a high-speed tram in Jerusalem and Haifa is the only metro line in the country with six stations connecting the lower city with the upper one.
It's basically an underground cable car.
Travelling by all kinds of public transport costs 6 shekels, for which you can drive 1.5 hours with a change.
In Israel, according to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated on Saturday.
From Friday evening until sunset on Saturday, he stops working in markets, shops and in public transport.
And on Sunday morning, the work week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and hotels you will only get kosher food: with the exception of pork, seafood, fish without scales and dishes that contain a combination of milk and meat.
They offer a large selection of dishes from lamb and beef, soups and desserts, prepared from coconut milk, traditional Jewish porridge hummus, various types of sauces, balls of ground chickpeas - falafel, fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs on the streets of Israeli cities.
However, there are a lot of well-fed cats that gracefully "wander to their own taste".
In the evening you can see them sleeping even on the roofs of parked cars.
Predecessor cats love crowded places and are eager to indulge in every delicacy.
Renting a car will cost from $37 per day (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80) per day.
Plus insurance - 15 dollars a day.
And renting a bike will cost about 15 shekels a day.
Tickets to the museum cost an average of 30 shekels.
Expressed in numbers
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
To get to know the country and relax came the most citizens of the USA, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine.
The country was visited by 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists from January to October 2012, which is 51% more than in the same period in 2010, before the abolition of visas on February 9, 2011.
"Great and powerful" will announce it to Moscow: emigrants will save money on language
While MPs and human rights defenders are still debating the law on compulsory language exams, there are already fraudsters in the country who sell "counterfeit" certificates
Every year, 13 million foreign workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn enough money to support families at home.
On December 1, the law came into force, according to which every working migrant will be required to pass the exam on knowledge of the Russian language.
So far, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the services sector, housing and communal services, lifestyle and retail.
FMS, however, promises that over time, relevant tests will be mandatory for all visitors.
However, the exams will consist not only of language skills, but also of Russian history and the foundations of law.
Knowledge of the language will also need to be confirmed in order to obtain and extend a work permit.
The exception applies only to citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
This law does not apply even to people who have successfully achieved certification and obtained an academic degree before the collapse of the USSR in 1991.
Benefit, Conviction and Protection of Rights
The network of test sites will work under the auspices of the Pushkin Institute of the Russian Language, the University of Friendship between Nations, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
Migrants can take exams in all cities; more than 160 such centers are already open in Russia.
The initiative to support the introduction of testing was also supported by deputies of the State Duma and the FMS (Federal Migration Service).
But before the law came into force, human rights defenders were able to ask the question in the press many times: what will it actually bring?
What will change the obligation to know the language for Russians and for the visitors themselves?
So, first of all - the representatives of the migration service answer - this will allow to reduce the number of people who suffer as a result of "slave labor."
Many people today talk about the protection of the rights of migrant workers, explains the Chairman of the Board of FMS of Russia in Tajikistan Viktor Sebelev.
The protection of their rights should be started before their departure.
Only the system of organized recruitment will allow 90% to solve the problems of foreign workers.
Problems arise in emigrants without a profession, without education, who do not know the language and do not have a medical examination.
Without knowledge of the language, Sebelev says with conviction, the future migrant is condemned to clashes with dishonest people who, under the pretext of helping him, will provide him with a "voucher" to terrible, cramped hostels, in which he and dozens of others like him will suffer for months without food and documents and work for 12 to 14 hours a day.
We receive many complaints from our migrant workers.
"In their homeland, they promise them one thing, but upon arrival, they cheat them, seize their passports, do not pay the promised wages," confirms Tolib Sharipov, head of the Tajik Labor Migration Agency.
Don't give up!
Moreover, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who intend to go to work in Russia recognize that they not only do not know the language of the country they want to get to, but they do not even have experience with this work.
Of course, this is not so much their fault as rather a misfortune: only very few Turkmens, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to get at least an adequate basic education.
After all, their families also need something to feed their children, not to mention the fact that they need to be properly dressed, dressed and equipped for school.
As children reach a productive age, they have to go to work at the first opportunity.
Without knowledge of the language, it is difficult - they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
It is true that, with regard to the Law on Language Examinations, human rights defenders point to one important point.
The tests will only be carried out on migrants who have a legal status.
If they don't have it, they won't even take the exams, and they won't get any more official work.
In the meantime, most migrant workers are still living illegally in Russia.
"Welcome, or Unauthorized Entry Banned"
Many of the incoming workers claim that getting official status in our country is not easy.
The reason - bureaucratic obstacles and all the language difficulties.
Legalization also costs money: from 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
But a fake registration can be obtained quickly and only one and a half thousand.
Russian police officers know that we basically have fake documents, without registration, and this leads to cases of blackmail.
"They require a hundred, two for cigarettes, tea," - shared with journalists about his experience the citizen of Tajikistan Umed Chushkadamov.
"Come on, don't be greedy, buy a painting"
On the first day of the language law, it was found that not only the registration documents of migrants are fake.
FMS employees have already confiscated several fake certificates of passing the language exam.
Counterfeit documents are printed on an ordinary color printer.
Of course, they did not get the new owners for free: each of the migrants, in the hope of making it easier for them to pass the tests, paid seven thousand rubles for this document.
This is two and a half times the amount of the official test: it will cost migrant workers three thousand rubles.
The main task of the near future is to secure the system against corruption so that workers cannot simply buy documents, which is what government officials and human rights defenders agree on.
So far, government authorities can promise foreign workers who failed the tests for the first time the necessary time to take a Russian language basics course.
Visitors who do not speak Russian are expected to work in areas where active interaction with people is not required.
The MVD (Ministry of the Interior) does not take into account the illegal arms market
The share of crimes with the use of legally held weapons is very low
The Ministry of Internal Affairs of Russia proposes to tighten the law in relation to the owners of civilian weapons.
It is the reaction of government authorities to recent events: the impetus was the cases of shootings at weddings that did not involve victims, and the massacre prepared by the Moscow lawyer Dimitri Vinogradov, which resulted in the deaths of seven people.
Police want to ban the carrying of dangerous weapons in public places and increase the age from which a license to carry weapons can be obtained - from 18 to 21 years.
This idea is supported by the head of the Duma Committee on Security and Anti-Corruption Irina Jarovaja, who promised that the amendments to the law on weapons will be submitted to the State Duma in the near future.
Not everyone is satisfied with the fact that the Russian state authorities are trying to deal with the problem by "tightening the screws".
An open letter appeared on the network, the authors of which - representatives of various social shooting organizations - demand the rejection of the "nonsensical tightening" of the law.
The percentage of hooliganism with registered weapons is minimal, Vasily Lesnikov, a lawyer and criminalist, told the BBC in an interview.
According to the statistics of the Ministry of the Interior, in six months of 2012, 142 crimes were committed using firearms registered by the bodies of the Ministry of the Interior, while in the same period a total of 1,168,000 crimes were committed.
The authors of the open letter are convinced that the tightening of legislation in the field of civilian weapons will not force the offender to switch to the "black" market.
According to them, at present, any weapon can be found in Moscow at a low price.
Currently, the Ministry of the Interior claims that the situation with the spread of illegal weapons is under control.
Suppliers: from races to officers
The "black" arms market is supplied by several channels.
There are five main channels, says retired colonel Victor Baranec, who worked for ten years in the workplaces of the Ministry of Education and the General Staff.
Screenshot of sites that accept weapon orders
The first of them - "army or military way", that is, a weapon that was stolen during the fighting in the Caucasus.
"The weapons were also stolen by Russian officers and the Caucasians themselves," Baranec said.
Another type of "black weapons" are weapons stolen by criminals from the representatives of the security forces.
Baranec explains that this includes thefts from police warehouses and weapons stolen directly from employees of law enforcement agencies.
Illegal "mainly" get on sale from military warehouses.
Explosions often occur in many military depots.
“It’s been proven that some of the fires were set deliberately – to cover up the shortage,” the former soldier said.
According to Barance, the arms manufacturers are also making their contribution.
“Currently, private arms companies are being created that are not competitive on the international market, and they are eliminating weapons that they supply to the black market, including Moscow,” the expert says.
Another source of the black market is smuggling.
A particularly large number of pistols and assault rifles come from poor countries, such as Kyrgyzstan.
"There is their production, sometimes weapons are produced here in small-scale production, and a mafia was created that organized their continuous production," explains the former soldier.
Where'd the gun come from?
Experts have summed up what is the approximate share of individual sources of supply of illegal weapons on the "black" market.
The report on this issue was prepared in 2011 by the Center for Problem Analysis and Public Administration Design.
Specialists analyzed the reports of the Ministry of the Interior and the Russian Statistical Office, criminological literature and data from public data portals focused on weapons.
The vast majority of illegal weapons, the researchers say, come from military and executive bodies.
