In recent days, there has been a wave of protests in America against low wages in Walmart hypermarkets and restaurants of popular fast food chains, such as McDonald’s, Burger King, Taco Bell, Wendy’s and Kentucky Fried Chicken.
So far, no one can predict whether this wave will turn into wave nine, or whether it is destined to disappear soon.
This action is supported by trade unions and a number of left-wing social organizations.
In addition to the modest salary increases made to regular workers at Walmart and in fast food systems, the goal of the protest organizers is to achieve the creation of trade unions in them.
At present, this economic sector is practically untouched by the trade union movement.
46 cents a year?
The events began last week after Thanksgiving, the so-called "Black Friday," when an orgy of cheap sales hit America, gripping millions of residents and in some cases accompanied by brawls.
On this day, Walmart, which employs 2.2 million people worldwide, left its workplaces and demonstrated alongside trade unions and left-wing activists at multinational chain companies whose goods are targeted at lower and middle-class people.
Walmart sells everything from diapers to hunting rifles and car batteries to vacuum cleaners, eggs and milk.
Products in its stores are on average 8% to 27% cheaper than in large supermarkets.
That’s why many low-wage employees at Walmart stores only shop at home at work.
The availability and range of products has made Walmart one of the largest companies in America.
According to critics, Walmart can afford to sell goods so cheaply partly because it pays very little to its employees.
They also complain about poor working conditions, such as the lack of automatic trucks or hand scanners.
Demonstrators on “Black Friday” demanded a pay rise and complained that the cost of health insurance provided by the company rose sharply from $30 to $100 a month.
A typical Walmart worker gets $9.5 an hour, but that doesn’t match the amount spent, employees say.
Researchers at the University of California, Berkeley, say that if Walmart raises the average wage to $12 an hour, it will cost the company $3.2 billion a year.
This is an average of 1.1% more than the company spends on salaries now.
If Walmart shifts the wage increase entirely to consumers, each visit to the store will cost only 46 cents more.
In one year, customers will spend approximately $12.39 more than they do today.
Walmart advocates point out that the protest took place in only nine countries, and the company should cause virtually no harm.
"Black Friday" in the company's stores lasted from 8 p.m. on Thursday until midnight the next day, and during this time, Walmart sold about 5,000 items of goods per second.
In total, its coffers made nearly 100 million transactions on Black Friday.
In an interview with the left-leaning Huffington Post, Dan Fogelman said that fewer than five Walmart employees had left their jobs, and that the protest was "another media sensation" organized by the unions.
"Unoccupied cash register!"
The protests continued this week in New York, where their target was not Walmart stores (those in that progressive city are not very popular, and therefore are almost not here), but "McDonald" and other cheap restaurants.
McDonald’s says it sells billions of servings, and then it doesn’t even pay you sick pay and doesn’t pay you properly for your honest work!
Jumaane Williams, member of the New York City Council
Currently, the minimum wage for work in accordance with federal laws and the regulations of the state of New York is 7.25 dollars per hour.
Fast food restaurants are gradually increasing this salary, but only slightly, and on average, their regular workers in New York receive $8.90 per hour.
In this expensive city, no one has a lower salary.
I don't understand how you can exist in New York for that kind of money.
Almost a quarter of American teenagers who work part-time behind the counter after school and live with their parents are employed at McDonald’s.
