At present, I constantly meet in an interview with McDonald's workers, who complain that they have to live on this money and sometimes even feed their children from it.
On the other hand, there is a comment on the Wall Street Journal forum, the author of which notes that it is irresponsible to have children if you do not know how to feed them.
Protesters, who began at 6:30 a.m. on Thursday at McDonald’s on 40th Street and Madison Avenue, demanded that cashiers and chefs at fast-food businesses start receiving at least $15 an hour, more than double their current minimum wage.
They also demanded that trade unions be established in the fast food sector.
U.S. law prohibits the administration from preventing the formation of trade unions and punishing activists of the trade union movement with harassment and dismissal.
On the other hand, management rarely makes their lives easier.
