Simply put, European legislation regulates how public contracts are to be dealt with, followed by individual national legislations and then by practice itself.
We put all this together, and even though the control is not yet complete, we found very interesting differences - in general, the legislation in our country is perhaps even "stricter and more perfect", but the practice itself is better in some parameters in Germany.
Thus, it is confirmed that it is not enough to create more and more precise rules, but it is necessary to devote oneself to the application of the law itself.
What can this project do for you, what does it do for you?
It is precisely such joint control that could help us to stop making efforts to tighten the laws, reduce and improve the limits, when this does not have such a positive impact.
Profitability means getting the corresponding thing at a reasonable (but not always the lowest) price, in order to avoid enrichment and possibly criminal behavior.
But by reducing the limit of orders, we do not necessarily achieve this.
Perhaps the system will be overwhelmed by so much "paper" that those who want to look for holes in the system will draw on it much easier than if the limit remained higher.
You are talking about domestic problems with translating public procurement legislation into practice.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is the office similar to our SAO, or is it set up differently?
As far as the authorities are concerned, just as the SAO operates the Bundesrechnungshof there, which is organised in a similar way to us, it also has a college, only it is formed in a slightly different way, but in principle both authorities are acting in a similar way.
The powers are also to some extent similar, but because Germany has a federal structure, so does these courts of auditors at the level of the individual federal states - in this the system is slightly different from ours.
BRH can control only federal money, represented by state funds.
Public funds, which are administered by the regions and municipalities in our country, are controlled there from the level of the federal accounting courts.
As for the legislation there, is it easier than ours?
In general, I would not like to compare it without specific data, however, in some respects Germany is usually referred to as a model, but it cannot be said for sure that it is better in everything.
Is it because they have better controllers?
Of course not, but again, I don’t like comparisons.
But it must be said that even the countries that we see as role models are facing a whole host of problems.
Otherwise, it would be useless for them to cooperate with our office, wouldn't it?
As far as the domestic legislation is concerned, what did the amendment to the Public Procurement Act mean for your office, are its effects already being manifested in any way?
Since the validity period of this amendment is relatively short, it is not yet manifested in our control actions.
Since we do ex-post checks, it is necessary to count on a certain delay.
So far, we are only observing this in the process of preparing future controls - we have launched our new tool 'risk detection of inefficiencies', through which we have driven almost 14,000 public contracts, and we have analysed them - there, of course, these changes will manifest themselves, because the limits will change, the conditions of some types of tendering will adjust, and so on.
Do you consider the approval of this law to be a benefit or a further burden on the system of bureaucracy?
I think this law is definitely a step in the right direction, and I hope it will be confirmed.
The problem that may arise here is that the rules will be "tightened" and it will not be possible to comply with them.
Already during the operation of the previous rules, the audited persons are obliged by the provider (for example, in the case of regional operational programmes by the regional council) to the fact that any failure to comply with the law on public procurement means a violation of budgetary discipline.
Is it worth it to tighten the law in this way?
I don't think so.
The system must exclude those who want to attack and abuse it, and not punish those who commit formal misconduct that has no impact on decision-making.
Such a system will only put more pressure on the bureaucracy.
So how do we get out of this?
Let's see where the road doesn't lead.
Recently, the Prime Minister said that the ODS will not bother entrepreneurs with checks of the so-called "Swarcsystem" - and what does this mean?
Is the Swarcsystem Prohibited or Allowed?
After all, the law must be somehow set up, and if it prohibits something, then even the Prime Minister cannot prevent the activity of the office, which is obliged to go to control and enforce duties.
He can say, "We're going to change the law and allow it," but he can't say we're going to do as nothing.
In the law on public procurement, there are quite strict rules on how what should be formally implemented - which is correct in order to protect public competition.
But on the other hand, it is tragic when the candidate with the best offer is excluded only for formal shortcomings.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct - this is what is lacking in our country in my opinion.
