Poland and space.
Last week, at the meeting of the ministers of the European Space Agency countries, Poland was accepted as the 20th member of the European Space Agency, as the second country from the countries of the former Eastern Bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on 12 November 2008).
Poland started close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and over the years has participated in a number of projects of the Agency.
However, Poland’s journey into space began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts had devoted themselves to space flights before World War II; but they did not always meet with understanding.
I will recall, for example, a lecture by A. Sternfeld at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory, which, on December 6, 1933, presented ideas from his pioneering work The Entrance to Cosmonautics.
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the audience cold, and after years Sternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Sternfeld was awarded the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize for his entry into space science in France.
Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great promoter of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He has published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and has written a number of books devoted to these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski became a world-famous promoter of cosmonautics, and his contribution was also appreciated by the fact that one of the craters on the far side of the Moon was named after him.
As early as 1925, a railway track was built in Poland, which was to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of the proposal is not known and the details of the project are not known.
It is not clear whether the missile was to be used to launch the dreadnought or to brake it.
Information about this dresiny is known only from the period press.
In 1933, the Polish artillery began to engage with missiles.
The research was carried out by the Cell of Armament Technology in cooperation with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfek and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzycki.
From the preserved materials it is clear that the research has reached the stage of practical tests.
However, with the arrival of the German troops, the research was interrupted.
In 1937, a proposal for a photoelectric fighter rocket appeared in the professional press, which was designed by an engineer Rohozinski, and the following year the work Rocket - Air Torpedo and Air Bomb by Leliwa-Krzywoblocky was published.
Both projects were intended for the military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) devoted all projects of military use of rocket technology to which all work was coordinated.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, its activities ended with the outbreak of war.
Other works devoted to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautical Society (Polish Astronautical Society).
For the first time, there is a mention of the company in the November 1954 issue of the magazine Problems, which contains four more comprehensive articles on astronautics.
In one of them, from Prof. M. Subotowicz, it is proposed to create a company that will deal with cosmonautics.
Projects of artificial satellites were already underway at that time, and it was clear that space research was a promising field.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) has been trying to join the International Astronautical Federation (founded in 1951), and already in the autumn, PTA became a full member.
The following year, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902-1959), the first chairman of the PTA, became vice-chairman of the International Astronautical Federation.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has been heavily involved in the development of the highly successful RM meteorological rocket (Meteorological Rocket), which became the first Polish rocket to conduct scientific research.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with an access of 1800 meters was about 80 cm long and its weight was less than 5 kg.
Later, an improved version of the RM-1A was built, and in the summer of 1959, flight tests of the two-stage RM-2 rocket began in the Bled Desert.
The rocket was 1.4 meters long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another type of development was to be capable of real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket was to have access to up to 14.5 km and its task was to monitor the high-altitude wind.
However, in 1962, further development was suspended.
The successor to the first RM rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, developed from 1962 to 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage, its total length was 510 cm and the starting weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types (marked Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which differed in the size of the space for scientific instruments.
In the Meteor-1A rocket was available space with a volume of 0.4 liters, Meteor-1B with a volume of 0.34 liters and Meteor-1C with a volume of 0.62 liters.
The maximum access for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Institute of Aviation, the first flight tests of which began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had a launch weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
Subsequently, versions of Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
It is necessary to mention the entry of Poland into COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of the COSPAR National Committee two years later.
Poland was also involved in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites as part of the Intercosmos program, and in 1978, Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladim<0xC3><0xAD>r Remek.
Repeal of the Public Works Act is not the solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court overturned the Public Works Act.
The resolution sparked a lively public debate.
It will certainly be interesting to look at the issue from a broader perspective.
Liberally oriented economic systems in the EU as well as in the globalized world are based on the principle of more, unregulated competition.
In its effect, this means that individual economic units, national economic systems, are in permanent conflict with each other.
The reason is the principle of free trade and the free, unrestricted movement of private capital, along with unbridled financial speculation.
Due to significant differences in the price of labor, (wages) price tensions occur.
Under this concept, it is necessary to understand the situation in which the manufacturer tries to compete with imports of cheap goods by "undercutting" the price of a competitor in order to take a larger share of the market and thus increase its own profits.
On a mass scale, this means for most entrepreneurs either to transfer production abroad, or to buy cheaply there, or to disappear.The result is high unemployment in countries where labor prices are high compared to other economies.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and thus no responsibility for the unemployment it produces, the social expenditure of the state necessarily increases.
The whole situation is amplified by the absolute reluctance of the masters of entrepreneurs to pay taxes and thus compensate for the economic and social social damage they have caused in the pursuit of profit.
The situation is so well known that it is not necessary to provide specific statistical data.
The ruthless practices of private capital create a situation in individual economies in which the governments of individual countries are forced to enter into competition with each other in order to artificially reduce the social level of their own population in order to attract foreign capital to the country.
In other words, governments give private capital a chance to its own population regardless of social decline.
This is mainly reflected in the changes to the current laws.
The aim is to economically force its own population to accept the price diktat of private capital, especially in the area of wages.
This is done, on the one hand, by a system of economic coercion in the case of long-term unemployment, and, on the other hand, by restricting the rights of employees in the field of labour law.
The result is growing poverty, along with increasing disparities between the poor and the rich.
For many years now, there have been public food outlets in Germany for the poor, who cannot afford their own work.
The number of these people is already in the millions.
In the context of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, it is quite common for well-employed people to be paid such a wage that the state has to pay them to the subsistence minimum.
Such a scandal was also reported in the case of auxiliary employees of the Bundestag.
The austerity measures of virtually all southern EU states undoubtedly lead to the same situation where people, under the pressure of a catastrophic fall in social standards, are forced to either emigrate, as was the case in the 19th century, or to live on the fringes of society in the hope that private investment capital may one day come to the country.
The question is, where does it come from?
If it is from other EU countries, then poverty will move from one country to another, or it will not come at all, because a Chinese, an Indian, a Brazilian, or a Turk, a Moroccan, or an Egyptian, or an African still work for a fraction of the European wage.
This applies to all of Latin America.
Liberal theory and the media obnoxiously claim that the state cannot participate in capital on its own economy, that a managed economy leads to economic disaster.
Private capital strongly insists that the state must not intervene in the economy through management interventions.
Then one has to ask whether private capital does not influence, in fact, now governs politics and thus the whole state in its own selfish sense.
Here's the clear answer, yes.
The proof is the existence of a virtually all-powerful and omnipresent lobby in all states.
The result is a desperate situation manifested in the field of corruption, the provision of mutual benefits, legislation, where practically everything is punishable, but nothing is criminal.
In the Federal Republic of Germany, the situation is such that the state ministries, due to lack of funds, entrust the drafting of laws to private law firms, which are often associated with industry.
These bills are then approved in the Bundestag.
All power in this way does not come from the people as proclaimed by Western-style constitutions, but from financially strong groups that prefer their own interests.
It is clear that liberal democracies are now rapidly getting into the situation described by Appianos in his Crisis of the Roman Republic under Caesar and Pompey: "The state has long been in complete disarray and the authorities have occupied themselves with violence.
For bribes, illegal gain of favor and with the help of stones or swords.
Bribery and corruption were rampant, and the people went to the polls with a pre-sold vote" ... "characteristic people did not apply for office at all, so one day as a result of this disruption was to stand without consuls for eight months ... "..The App really began to talk about the fact that the only remedy in a bad situation is self-government and that it is necessary to control it.
As in ancient times, modern society is based on a ruthless preference for self-interest, regardless of the interests of society as a whole.
By its very nature, private capital is no longer able to understand and apply the benefits of society as a whole.
The result now, as then, is an unprecedented decadence of elites without any attempt at reform of a deeper nature.
The causality of the rise of fascist and communist regimes must therefore be sought in the ruthless liberalization of the economic systems of the 19th and 20th centuries.
In the current state of affairs, the demise of these systems in favor of liberal-type democracy can be considered a certain break with the expectation of the next round.
Particularly disastrous is the fact that today’s elites completely ignore in the future the possible hundreds of thousands of deaths, humanitarian and social catastrophes that we are already witnessing, along with crimes against humanity, as we know them from old and new history.
The repeal of the Public Works Act is not a solution, at least not a permanent one.
Under the pressure of competition at both international and European level, the government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to look for ways to further reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is systemic.
The solution is targeted political and social reforms that will strengthen the capital participation of the state in the economy, strengthen the influence of citizens on the government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
