Argo: When it's worst, call Hollywood
In November 1979, a mob of Islamist students seized the U.S. embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the ousted Shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who fled to the United States after the revolution, which had been the patron of his regime for decades.
For the US administration, the situation did not offer a positive starting point - to throw the Shah overboard could not afford, because it would fundamentally threaten the confidence of allies in other countries.
But the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution resulted in the establishment of a theocratic regime, was not achieved.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which was later deepened by the fiasco of the attempt to free the hostages by force.
The imprisoned diplomats were eventually released after 444 days, after negotiations were brokered by the Algerian government.
Their fate at home has sparked a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiment.
The debacle in Iran contributed significantly to Jimmy Carter's loss to Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
Directed by Ben Affleck, Argo chronicles one episode of the story that brought America a small victory.
Just before the occupation of the embassy, six employees fled from it.
After a difficult period, they ended up in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in cooperation with Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran, helped by an extravagant cover story - they left for Canadian passports as members of the film crew, which in the country was inspecting the location for the filming of a sci-fi movie.
Combination of genres
The plan, devised by "exfiltration" expert Tony Mendez, also called for Hollywood's cooperation.
In order for the legend to be credible, it was written about the film project in specialized magazines, press conferences were held, a fictional production company had a real office.
The details of the operation have been kept secret for a long time, the film is based on the memoirs of Tony Mendez.
Affleck’s film is a special combination of several genres.
On the one hand, a realistically conceived political thriller, at the same time the so-called "caper movie", the story of a successful piece, a prank - an example can be a series of Danny's partners.
The film thus alternates moods - on the one hand documentary sequences from Tehran (the title sequence shows iconic period photographs of events and the way in which the same situations were presented in the film - there are no big differences in this).
On the other hand, lightened passages from Hollywood, reconciled with irony and slight exaggeration.
And then there's scenes from CIA headquarters and other institutions -- men in suits discussing the situation at the negotiating tables, in the corridors of the office, on the phone...
Ben Affleck managed to restart his career in a remarkable way.
The derided actor became a respected director and even his acting ceased to be the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film, after the dark crime drama Gone Baby Gone (2007) and the thriller City (2010).
At the same time, it is the first Affleck film that does not take place in the director’s home city of Boston.
The feeling for the atmosphere of the place was one of the characteristics that raised the director’s older films above the Hollywood standard.
And Affleck shows it in Argo, where Tehran "plays" Canada.
The best scenes in the film take place in the streets, in the reconstruction of real events - the opening sequence of the fall of the embassy is impressive in its clarity, which at the same time conveys the emotion of confusion and unpredictability that occur when history suddenly moves somewhere.
Affleck and his collaborators achieve a similar effect in fictional scenes (a fake staff in a Tehran bazaar).
Too many things in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story does not offer much in the cinematic sense of the exciting scenes.
Quite successfully working with this little, sometimes he comes up with something to the reality - everything does not work out so elegantly there (a scene in which the impending crisis at the Tehran airport turns away a phone call in America and the chase after the runway seems quite drawn to the hair).
The weakness of Arga, however, is the dispersion resulting from the need to show too many events in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in the roles of Hollywood collaborators, but their characters would deserve more space and are not the only ones in the film.
Affleck’s film loses a bit of a dramatic turn, it is a film that can be watched with a slight interest, appreciate the realization and retro style that evokes the thrillers of the 70s.
But it's hard to pull off.
As a reminder of a still-living history, and a testament to how exaggerated the notions of omnipotent and omniscient secret services are, but enough.
