The server www.bankovnipoplatky.com, which annually publishes a survey on the most absurd bank fee, has now decided to announce a competition for "the most absurd regulations or ideas from the EU workshop".
"We were led to this by the last event, when the EU plans to adopt a 40 percent quota for women in the management of large European companies," said Patrik Nacher, the organizer of the survey.
Among the nominated absurdities is, for example, the recent decision of the European Court of Justice to unify the rates of insurance premiums for men and women.
So far, women have been favored in life insurance prices because they are objectively less risky for insurance companies.
"Other incredible ideas from the EU workshop can be nominated by people by the end of this year.
The vote itself will then take place until the end of February 2013,” Nacher said.
Controversial EU regulations include mandatory incorporation of biocomponents into fuels, which is harmful to nature, a ban on the use of reliable mercury thermometers just because they contain a relatively small amount of a dangerous substance, or a directive on the size of chicken cages, which has made eggs significantly more expensive this year.
Earlier, criticism was also faced by the de facto ban on the use of the term butter spread or the exclusion of classic light bulbs from sale.
High-quality bananas should be 14 centimeters
The EU apparatus often makes decisions under the pressure of one or another commercial or industrial lobby, whose demands in Brussels are usually defended by a state or a group of states (so the Czech Republic is now also enforcing the demands of its banks with the threat of a veto).
Interests of the lobby were also due to the fact that, for example, bananas of the highest quality had to reach a length of at least 14 cm in the Union and were not allowed to show "anomalous curvature".
In doing so, the European Commission has defended itself by merely harmonising the hitherto divergent national standards that have complicated trade.
Fruit and vegetable standards have already been softened by the EU, despite the resistance of some countries, pointing out that existing directives lead to food waste.
Last year’s EU regulation may also be a candidate to win the poll, according to which it is mandatory for inflatable balloons sold to be notified that children under the age of 8 are not allowed to inflate without adult supervision.
The EU has cited U.S. research showing that balloons between toys are the leading cause of child deaths from suffocation.
A similar restriction now applies to children under 14 years of age when blowing into pilgrimage stalls.
Curious ideas are born at home
The rule concerning the European officials themselves is also quite absurd - anyone who has an official function in the EU cannot use the name of Macedonia, given the sensitivity of the topic for Greece, and must instead speak about FYROM (Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia).
The server Bankovn<0xC3><0xAD>poplatky.com in cooperation with the association of liberal economists Laissez Faire nominated to the survey, in addition to some of the above absurdities, the EU regulations on the volume of food stocks in the territory of a Member State.
The EU has set the maximum quantities of food stocks that could have been on the territory of the Czech Republic on the day of our accession to the Union.
The Czech Republic then exceeded, for example, the prescribed volumes for canned mushrooms, for which it was threatened with a high fine.
The organizers of the survey were also interested in the idea of paying some countries for not having the sea, and the idea of granting subsidies on request for obtaining a subsidy.
However, these ideas did not originate in Brussels, but in Prague.
"We are handicapped by the fact that we do not have the sea.
We will ask the European Union for a refund," said Jaroslav Palas, the then Minister of Agriculture (<0xC4><0x8C>SSD), in autumn 2004.
As an argument, he said that a lot of grain was produced in our country and as a result of so-called intervention purchases, the state should have full warehouses, which it had to export.
The EU, according to Palas, should have paid us hundreds of millions of euros for the Czech Republic’s continued access to ports.
The European Commission finally welcomed the Czech Republic by organizing a tender for the purchase of grain from countries that do not have access to the sea.
The subsidy for obtaining the subsidy was offered to the municipalities by the Ministry for Regional Development managed by Minister Pavel Nemec (US-DEU), specifically they were supposed to write a request for subsidies from Brussels.
EU: Bizarre regulations are an exception
Although the regulations are easily criticized in the Member States, the EU's efforts to regulate and, at the same time, to operate and develop the whole Union more effectively deserve more recognition, according to a number of experts.
A more serious problem, according to experts, is, for example, the use of EU subsidies for projects that have nothing to do with deepening European integration, but which were forced upon themselves by the Member States during the budget negotiations.
The emotion among the Czechs is also aroused by the fact that, like other countries of the Union, the Czech Republic must fight in Brussels for the right to a specific designation of its traditional products, and it will not always succeed in this match.
After a six-year struggle with the Germans and Austrians, the Czechs defended the designation of Olomouc curds, but the domestic rum, whose tradition dates back to the 19th century in our country, had to be renamed by our producers to the local brand.
The naming of rum can only be carried by products from cane distillate, and not from sugar beet.
In the official list of EU registered products in the company of world-famous feta and gorgonzola cheeses, marzipan from German L<0xC3><0xBC>beck or Parma hams, for example, Karlovy Vary biscuits, Pogorelicky and T<0xC5><0x99>ebo<0xC5><0x88> carp and <0xC5><0xBD>atec hops have already been included.
Pardubice gingerbread and mustard pipes can also be a trademark of the EU.
