Spijkenisse, a housing estate close to Rotterdam without its own jobs that are not worth visiting, holds a special record.
With a population of 80,000, this municipality has the lowest level of education in the whole of the Netherlands.
In order to solve this stupid situation, a few years ago the decision was made to contribute to the general education and to build seven nicely painted reinforced concrete miniatures of fictitious bridges, which are depicted on euro banknotes.
But the success of the educational offensive was not at all dizzying.
And so the city councillors realized that there was only one way to become masters of statistics: we had to have a library!
Winy Maas of Rotterdam’s MVRDV architectural studio, a master of insanely bold column graphs and maker of funny, often even cynical, constructions, accepted the matter with the usual calmness and appeared at the 2003 competition with five books under his arm and a grin on his face.
And while the commission was still looking around in amazement and shrugging its shoulders, the brazen Maas was making his gifts on himself according to his size, and he ended his activist-justified speech with the words, "Dear urban communities!"
So this is my proposal for the Mountain of Books in Spijkenisse, the so-called Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>30 million mountain was completed.
It is part of a revitalization project, which also includes an underground parking lot, a supermarket, a post office and several adjacent residential and terraced houses with a total of 50 apartments.
At the beginning of November, the Mountain of Books was awarded the second place "Best Library of NL 2012".
The project is also nominated for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
Small-town grey, which so far could not offer more than a postmodern pedestrian zone and an unusually ugly town hall, behind whose white facade you would rather expect a dairy, is thanks to this it is richer in a bit of contemporary architecture.
Above all, however, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in the history of its existence.
A Long Way to the Book
First impression: the reader's Eldorado under the cheese lid.
There is an elevator in the middle of the mountain massif, but you will discover your true spatial and reading passions only when you walk through the topography.
From all sides, the glazed interior is bright and clear, the floor of the burnt cabr<0xC3><0xAD>n and the elegant street lantern clearly express the atmosphere of the public square.
The urban environment is perfect.
You see park benches, a dog and boys and girls playing football.
And everywhere books, books, books.
“Normally there are bookshelves along the facade, and in the middle is a large dark space, which is mostly uncomfortable and impersonal,” says Winy Maas.
We built the classic spatial configuration upside down and pushed the space for readers from the inside out.
The interior of the Mountain of Books is cleverly used: in the center there are offices, an Internet library, a chess club, an ecological center and a headquarters of home technology.
A special pleasure is the black bookshelves, which are one wall cladding, one window sill and another staircase railing.
Appearance, structure and smell are foreign.
Over the unknown building material, even committed architects and construction engineers twist their heads.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials here," says Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, when asked by Standard magazine.
And so one day, at a farm in Friesland, we came across a suitable agricultural waste product.
For many years, in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands, a millimeter fleece of synthetic matter has been used as a base under the roots.
It is cheap and time efficient.
Thin textiles last for one, two seasons and then are ripe for disposal into bulky waste.
For the library, the fleece - for the first time in such quantity - was pressed on plates four centimeters thick.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the so-called Landbouwplastic (KLP) turns into a dark, homogeneous and load-bearing material that smells a little like a new car and a little like sports shoes.
After 105 steps you will reach the top.
At the end of the nearly 500-meter-long journey, you will be rewarded not only with fantastic views of the city, but also with Dutch croquettes and figs in pots.
They take care of the atmosphere, but mainly the correct humidity in the mountains of literature.
Gifts for a new soul
"You might not believe it, but this house is a model project in terms of ecology, despite the many glass surfaces," says Trouborst.
It heats and cools with the earth's heat.
Although the Mountain of Books stands under a glass lid, the sun shines in only briefly, even on sunny days.
Wide glued wooden truss, which stands perpendicular to the glazed facade, serves as a shading and captures a large part of the sun's radiation.
The climate in the room is very pleasant.
They can handle the rest of the fully automatic blinds.
