Lisette Verhaig was already there.
And traditional Chinese medicine teacher Cynthia Bogarde, who even refers to Boekenberg as Spijkenisse’s “long-awaited soul.”
The reason: every resident of the city was invited to the opening a few weeks ago to donate one book from his personal fund.
The optical gaps in the not yet fully equipped library, which currently has 70,000 items, were to be filled first.
The concept has proven itself.
The shelves are full.
“There is nothing worse than a half-empty library,” says architect Winy Maas.
"I think that thanks to our invitation, now every resident has a certain relationship with the new house.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it's just for decoration.
Thus, MVRDV succeeded in the royal discipline, which in professional jargon is called identity formation.
Spijkenisse wrote the history of literature.
No matter how young and uneducated he is.
This is the starting point for identity.
