Australia’s ugly tobacco and cigarette packaging laws, the world’s first of their kind, have come into force, replacing the brand’s logos and colors with generic olive-green boxes with hideous images of diseased body parts and images of children and newborns sickened by their parents’ smoking.
In addition to various health warnings and pictures, mandatory from Saturday, the only difference between the boxes are brand names that are printed in the same small font.
This is the strictest regime in the world regarding tobacco packaging.
The Australian federal government claims that the goal is to discourage young people from smoking by ridding them of their attraction.
It relies on studies that show that if people do not start smoking by the age of 26, there is a 99% chance that they will never start smoking.
