In a world of constant connectivity, it’s not so bad to be bored
The last Thanksgiving I unexpectedly spent five hours at the airport when our plane was in mechanical trouble and we had to wait for the arrival of another plane.
So I had a lot of time to think about boredom.
I'm not gonna lie to you.
Waiting half a day at the airport for the next flight is pretty annoying, despite the distractions of books, magazines and iPhones (not to mention duty-free shops).
But some scientists and experts on child development are increasingly coming up with praise for boredom.
They say that it is good for us (and our children) to get bored sometimes.
It forces the brain to go in interesting directions, which can encourage creativity.
And since most of us are constantly connected to some screen nowadays, we don’t have a chance to enjoy the boredom.
Should we encourage boredom?
Yes, sir.
Oh, no.
But I'll come back to that.
First, like many people, I assumed that boredom was a relatively new phenomenon that occurred with the advent of more free time.
But as Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada, says, he is the author of Boredom: A Lively History (Yale University Press, 2011).
"In fact, boredom has a long history," he said.
On the walls in Pompeii was found a Latin inscription concerning boredom, dating from the first century AD.
And then there's the question of how we define boredom.
The problem is that it has been defined and discussed in many different ways, said John D. Eastwood, a professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada.
After viewing the research literature and presenting the idea to a target group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as the experience of “wanting to do something that would satisfy me, but not being able to do it.”
Boredom differs from apathy in that the person is not involved in anything, but would like to be.
He says there's no compulsion in apathy to do anything.
He says that the core of boredom is "disruption of the attention process associated with a bad mood and a sense of slowly passing time."
Boredom can be a lot like depression.
But Professor Eastwood said that while they may have a relationship, bored people tend to see the problem as an environment or a world, while depressed people see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think we’re bored when we’re just having trouble concentrating.
In their study, “The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention,” published in September in Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and colleagues pointed to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a tape of a person reading an article from a journal.
Some groups heard a loud and unrelated TV program in the next room, others heard it so quietly that they barely noticed it, while the third group did not hear it at all.
Those who heard the TV program silently reported more boredom than the other two groups — they had trouble concentrating, but they weren’t sure why, and attributed the trouble to boredom.
When you’re trying to focus on a difficult or engaging task, distraction can lead to boredom, said Mark J. Fenske, a professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the study’s authors.
On the other hand, when you’re doing something boring, “like finding the wrong parts on the factory line, distracting music can help you not get bored.”
In fact, he said, we now know that twisting and scribbling, which is often seen as a sign of boredom, can actually help fight boredom and keep people physically more alert.
“Research shows that children who are allowed to wobble learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to sit still,” said Professor Fenske.
We've all experienced boredom at some point - the delay of my flight, the humming speaker, a particularly lengthy film.
Some people are more likely to get bored than others.
To help measure boredom, scientists developed the Boredom Proneness Scale in the 1980s.
The scale includes questions such as, “A lot of the things I have to do are repetitive and monotonous,” and “I have so many interests that I don’t have time to do them all.”
Using these scales, researchers found that boys tend to get bored more often than girls, said Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, especially when it comes to the need to have more and different external stimuli.
Teenagers, however, are generally inert.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and social development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day.
He found that 32 percent of teens said they were bored at school and doing homework, while 23 percent said they were bored when they weren’t at school.
On the other hand, 3 percent of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson said he did not know whether the percentage of boredom would be now, 21 years later, higher or lower.
But he said he knows that “adolescence is a peak time for boredom,” which is largely due to children and youth not being given much control over what they want to do.
So back to my original question: “Is boredom good for you?”
As research shows, sometimes not, because in its extreme form it can lead people to take absurd physical risks, gamble or abuse addictive substances as a way to mitigate it.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers have discussed the connection between boredom and creativity, said Professor Vodanovich, who has studied the problem for more than two decades.
“Boredom is the brain’s way of telling you that you should be doing something else,” said Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at NYU.
But the brain doesn’t always know the most appropriate thing to do.
If you get bored and use this energy to play guitar and cook, it will make you happy.
However, if you watch TV, it will only make you happy for a while, not for the long term.
So if your child is bored and you give him an iPad, he won’t be bored anymore, but he won’t learn how to entertain himself or drive himself, Professor Fenske said.
And "this separate management is transferred from one situation to another," the professor said.
Your child will not only learn how to entertain themselves, but will gain more self-control in other areas.
I don't think we really want to celebrate boredom.
But we shouldn't be too critical of it either.
Rather, our goal should be to feel comfortable when we are out of the reach of constant buzzing activity and technology.
Professor Eastwood agreed.
"We blame it on the need to be bored even more, but boredom is a painful, restless desire to be connected to something meaningful," he said.
What people are actually looking for, he said, is a way to relax and enjoy your free time.
"In an environment where we're constantly overstimulated," he said, "it's hard to find ways to entertain yourself when the noise goes off."
In Colorado, there is no guide to the new marijuana law.
