In the uncertain weeks following the Colorado vote to legalize small amounts of marijuana for recreational use, the answer to hundreds of smaller drug cases depends on the place rather than the law.
Hundreds of cases of marijuana possession offenses have already been dropped here and in the state of Washington, which has approved similar measures.
The police department has stopped blaming adults aged 21 and older for holding a small amount that will be legally allowed once the law enters into force in the coming weeks.
But prosecutors in Colorado’s more conservative counties have said they will pursue existing marijuana cases, and are still accusing people of possession.
At the same time, several cities from suburban Denver toward the Western Mountains are voting to prevent the opening of new, state-licensed marijuana stores in their communities.
“This thing is going so fast that I don’t know what’s going to happen next,” said Daniel J. Oates, a police chief in the city of Aurora, east of Denver.
Regulators in the state of Washington are also cracking their heads.
And they're looking for guidance on how to set up a licensing system for growing, producing, distributing and selling - all by December 1, 2013.
They say Colorado, for better or worse, is ahead of most states in regulating marijuana, first for medical use and now for recreational use.
“Colorado has a more regulated market, so it will be a good lead,” said Brian E. Smith, spokesman for the Washington State Alcohol Licensing Board.
But as Mr. Smith admitted, no place or system can do more than suggest what might work.
“There is no real precedent that we can follow,” he said.
The Washington Act, known as the I-502, takes effect on December 6, which also leaves an annual vacuum during which there will not yet be a state licensing system, but legal possession does.
And there are tricky mechanical issues that need to be resolved during this time, such as how to balance a state directive on “appropriate access” to licensed marijuana with its ban on the cannabis trade within 330 meters of schools, parks, playgrounds or children’s centers.
“Nowhere will it be more difficult to locate a licensed cannabis trade than in urban areas, especially in the Seattle metropolitan area,” said Ben Livingston, a spokesman for the Center for Legal Cannabis, a recently founded research group.
On November 21, Chief Oates of Aurora City sent an email to his officers informing them that the city prosecutor would no longer prosecute offenses for possession of small amounts of marijuana by any citizen over the age of 21 and that the police would “immediately” stop blaming people for these crimes.
Chief Oates said police will enforce city laws regulating medical marijuana growers and will continue to prosecute drug traffickers and dealers.
In Weld County, northern Colorado, District Attorney Ken Buck presents a stricter view.
After the vote, he said his office would continue to prosecute marijuana possession cases, mostly as a way to pressure users to seek treatment.
Currently, 119 people are facing charges of possession of 56 grams or less of marijuana, although many are facing further charges.
“Our office is required to prosecute criminal offenses that were criminal offenses at the time they occurred,” Buck said in a statement.
The response has been complicated in places like rural Mesa County, where voters have rejected a marijuana initiative.
Police in Grand Junction, the county's largest city, no longer charge adults with possession of small quantities.
The district attorney, Pete Hautzinger, supports this decision but has also decided not to dismiss all pending possession cases.
"I don't think I'm wasting my time continuing to enforce the law until it changes," he said.
Although 55 percent of Colorado voters supported the measure, bringing recreational marijuana into the hands of the government and the legal system will never be easy.
And conflicting responses across the state revealed deep divisions among local officials in the face of this great state green experiment.
For district attorneys, it’s a “cultural barrier,” said Sean McAllister, a Denver lawyer who represents defendants in marijuana possession and a local spokesman for the National Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws.
“They have spent so much of their lives prosecuting people that they still can’t really accept that it’s legal,” he said.
As the first states to treat small amounts of marijuana as alcohol, Colorado and Washington are on track to become national drug-legalization test cases.
Advocates and state authorities are planning new boundaries for legalized sales while also anxiously awaiting orders from the federal government, which still plans to consider the sale and cultivation of marijuana as federal crimes.
Advocates of marijuana legalization hope the Justice Department will give in.
Despite several arrests of medical marijuana sellers and patients who use it that have attracted attention, the federal government has largely kept medical marijuana stores in Colorado, Washington, and 16 other states open.
While anti-drug agents are unlikely to slam the door to catch a small bag of drugs, they are likely to resist allowing state-regulated recreational marijuana trades allowed under the new laws, said Kevin A. Sabet, a former drug policy adviser to the Obama administration.
Several Colorado cities are not waiting for federal action.
Even before the election day, some local governments had approved moratoriums on any new marijuana trades, though it would still take about a year before any trade could open.
Last week, the western city of Montrose proposed a six-month ban and is likely to go into effect next week.
“We don’t want to be in a situation where we’re going to license someone and then we’re going to have a big federal issue,” said Bob Nicholson, a member of the city council.
Our community voted against this amendment.
