There are a lot of questions.
Petronella Wyatt: “I was forced to leave Oxford because I am a conservative.”
It is not just today’s university students who are being attacked for their opinions.
I don't remember ever dreaming about going to Oxford University.
Both my father and my older brother studied at what I thought was the world’s largest seat of knowledge, a modern, rambling Greek symposium motivating the two pillars of civilization, free thought and tolerance.
So far, in the late 1980s, within two weeks of attending Worcester College, where I wanted to study history, I packed my bags and plunged into the first scandal of my life.
My father collapsed and cried.
My friends were confused.
The Evening Standard claimed that I gave up because I objected to loving students in the next room.
Writer A. N. Wilson famously said that I left because I was forced to drink from battered mugs.
The truth was less comical.
I ran away.
Yes, I escaped because I was subject to systematic bullying and intimidation.
Not because of my rather bizarre name or the fact that I came from a private school.
I was persecuted for only one reason, and in this cradle of supposed enlightenment it was both bigoted and barbaric: my father, the late Woodrow Wyatt, was a senior adviser to Margaret Thatcher, and I was a Conservative supporter.
You may be wondering why I'm bringing this up now.
Simply because recent reports suggest that a new generation of students to the right of the middle are suffering similar persecution.
The institutionalized and growing hatred of conservative students at Oxford is so great that last week a group of these students called for the same protection of equal rights as gays, disabled people and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of the junior class association (JCR) at Corpus Christi College say that because of their political views, they are “often actively isolated, exposed to personal attacks, and shown that they are not welcome.”
They call for the creation of a position on the university's Equal Opportunities Committee to ensure that they are free to express their views.
Their situation was not helped by the recently-released BBC Two documentary programme Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right about student political events, which portrayed conservatives as oddballs and neo-Nazis.
The show featured graduate Joe Cooke, former president of the Oxford University Conservative Association (OUCA), who rode a Rolls-Royce, was dressed in a silver suit and had a silver-headed staff.
At other universities, conservative students say they are being treated like “sacrificial lambs” because of the introduction of higher tuition.
Twenty-year-old Luke Black, vice president of the Nottingham University Conservative Association, told a Sunday newspaper that “leftist influence in universities is growing.
People think we’re like the Bullingdon Club without meeting us at all.”
Corpus Christi’s 21-year-old history student Samuel Roberts, who is behind the movement for greater protection, says such a climate is “unpleasant,” while 19-year-old OUCA president-elect Stephanie Cherill says there has been a deterioration in JCR members’ approach to people on the right from Wednesday.
“This poses a threat to the atmosphere of intellectual discussion, as well as to the well-being of members,” he says.
During my first few weeks at Oxford, I was a one-member minority.
I joined in September 1986, 18 years old and paralyzingly shy.
Hatred for the Conservative Party was most bitter.
A year earlier, the university voted to refuse to award an honorary degree to former student Margaret Thatcher because of cuts in funding for higher education.
From the atmosphere, even the Stalinists would shudder with apprehension.
During the first few days of the opening week, when the new students meet each other and the professors, I got to taste the wormwood that was to come.
I have found that not only do professors tacitly approve of the bullying of conservative students, but they also participate in it with gusto.
A policy of mining strike, privatization, and government resistance to apartheid sanctions in South Africa was brought into the wood-paneled auditoriums.
My first lecture concerned the translation of an 18th-century French text into English, and I was unprepared for what followed.
"Miss Wyatt," said Professor Harry Pitt (now deceased), "please translate the first paragraph."
I've been going through a lot of grief.
Professor Pitt, a little man with a face like cake dough, was very gally.
"Are the Thatchers refusing to learn French, or are they just stupid?" he asked.
The other students shrugged.
There were tears in my eyes.
"I suggest you take some basic French lessons in your spare time, unless you're too busy with social affairs," said Professor Pitt.
Frustrated, I returned to my room.
At dinner at school, I was sitting alone when I felt a slight tap on my shoulder.
He was a second-year student named James, who introduced himself as a member of OUCA.
"I know who you are," he said kindly.
I'm afraid that's the case.
Anyone suspected of conservatism is a target.
It's bad enough for me, but they know your father's close to Margaret Thatcher, so it's gonna get worse for you.
Most conservative freshmen pretend to be Labour.
Later, in a local pub, I cowardly tried to pretend.
I insisted that I didn't agree with everything Thatcher said.
This trick proved to be unsuccessful.
A first-year student in philosophy, politics, and economics who (what an irony) went to Eton said, "You are the daughter of a fascist pig."
You're infected.
The other students took notes with him.
I was sick, dirty.
"How do conservatives love each other?" one asked.
They beat each other up, don't they?
I felt the way homosexuals must have felt before the liberal legislation of the 1960s.
Could I ever lead a normal life in Oxford?
Would I be forced to meet like-minded people only after dark?
Would I have to turn into a labourer and suppress my natural inclinations?
For three years, I had developed a purgatory of ignorance and isolation.
The only openly conservative professor was Norman Stone, a professor of modern history who resided at my faculty.
He was hated not only for being conservative, but also for being Margaret Thatcher’s foreign policy adviser and one of her speechwriters.
He was almost there.
He hated the place for its wickedness and pettiness, and for its penchant for the Marxist-determinist view of history.
In 1997 he became a professor at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
"You won't be happy here," he told me.
I began commuting from Oxford to my parents’ house in London, seeking refuge with my disinterested metropolitan friends and family.
I told my father I hated Oxford and why.
He couldn't believe it.
During his studies at Oxford in the 1940s, all political views were accepted.
"But it's the best place in the world," he said pathetically.
They wouldn't do that, not in a city of dreamy moods.
Even my communist friends have always had perfect manners.
His wet eyes dimmed.
Try it again.
I'm sure it's just a joke.
It would break my heart if you left.
Exhausted by frequent trips to London, my emotional resilience deteriorated.
My friend, also a supporter of the Conservative Party, succumbed to pressure and gave up his convictions.
The following week, while teaching, when another professor of history declared in all seriousness that I was the "enemy of the people," I decided to do the same.
Even though I blushed with shame inside, I admitted that "my parents brainwashed me" and called them "old fools".
The relief was only short-term.
The nail in the coffin of my Oxford career was hammered by my father.
At the time, he wrote two columns a week in Murdoch's newspaper.
My door was locked.
I crouched inside, and after five minutes, my pursuers gave up.
When they left, I packed my suitcase and caught the first train to London.
I never came back.
You can call me a snot-nosed weakling.
But no 18-year-old girl or boy should be subject to such intimidation and poisoning in an educational institution.
Even more tragic, however, is that it was Oxford, from which not only 14 conservative prime ministers emerged, but which also to this day hides behind the undeserved reputation of a place with equality and freedom of thought.
