The world's toughest craft: sulfur carriers in the Kawah Ijen region
For four euros, the bearers in the Indonesian volcano area are gambling with their lives and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulfur down steep stone paths.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and there are those who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anta Wijayi, one of the 400 miners who make a living by mining sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, they must fly every day to the bottom of the crater, where sulfur gases escape from the interior of the Earth, and when in contact with air, it passes into a solid state.
After cutting large blocks of sulfur, which together weigh up to 70 kilograms, he carries them on his shoulders in two bamboo baskets along steep stone paths.
To the summit of the volcano, which rises 2,386 meters, it is only 250 meters, but the exhausted carriers take over 40 minutes to climb the turtles at a rate of up, as they maintain balance and carefully consider their steps so as not to slip and collapse into the abyss.
They know that any trip could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who fell from the cliffs of Kawah Ijen years ago.
The miners in Kawah I only earn five cents for every kilo of sulfur they mine.
When they are at the top, they make their way around tourists who photograph them as if they were monkeys in a circus, and wearily carry heavy baskets to the weight that the mining company placed a little lower, at an altitude of 1850 meters.
PT Candi Ngrimbi has been mining the volcano since 1960 and has never paid its workers more than 662 Indonesian rupees (five cents) per kilo of sulfur.
Then it sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to the petrochemical industry, as this mineral has its place in everyday life and is used for the production of matches, fun pyrotechnics, cosmetics, dynamite and even for the bleaching of sugar.
“Because we normally carry 70 kilos, we earn about 46,000 rupees (<0xE2><0x82><0xAC>3.8) for each trip,” explains Anto, who usually completes three trips a day.
