Singapore is looking for babies to save the economy
Singaporeans are seduced by the fact that they do not have children, by career, stress and the cost of living and education.
"Singapore's population needs to grow."
I'm married and I'm a patriot, you're my wife and you're a patriot.
It may seem incredible that this slogan is part of a menthol candy ad, but still – or perhaps because of it – the video went viral on YouTube earlier this year in Singapore.
These sentences are part of a rap that uses local cues like “put a bun in the oven” as a mockery of Singapore’s birth rate.
Advertising agency BBH, which created the video, hopes that they will be able to draw attention to the problem in a funny way with this advertisement.
The agency’s artistic director, Douglas Hamilton, said he wanted to use the influence of music to make people fulfill “their civic duty.”
“It’s all about the internet, so it must have been fun and funny.
This is the biggest problem in this country.
We are the worst in the world at reproducing our population, so we felt it was a topic we had to touch.
We knew that the government was trying to do a lot of things like expand perfumes with pheromones or organize dating parties.
Many of these ideas may have been creative, but not entirely functional.
So we thought, why not do the most creative thing possible, like rap composition, to solve this problem."
1.2 children
Anyone who doesn’t take it lightly is the Singaporean government.
It spends $1,300 a year to encourage citizens to have more children.
The government’s marriage and family package provides up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave, and allocates financial benefits.
However, all these measures had little effect.
Singapore is a wealthy city-state with advanced technology in Southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its officials and strict social controls.
The birth rate in Singapore with regard to the stratification of the population is currently 1.2 children per woman.
The last time the birth rate exceeded the value of 2, which is considered the rate of recovery, was in 1976.
Why don’t Singaporeans have more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of the marriage and family department at the National Population Authority, said it was because of “better education” and a “broader range of career opportunities.”
“People have a wider range of options when it comes to life goals and priorities, it’s not just about marriage and family,” he explains.
These changes in social norms have contributed to an increase in the number of single people and to the postponement of marriage and childbirth, resulting in a decrease in the birth rate in Singapore.
While there have been efforts under immigration policy to drastically increase the influx of immigrants as a measure against population decline, this has caused resentment among locals.
On some Singaporean websites, there is undisguised xenophobia against many new immigrants, particularly Chinese, who are criticized for keeping wages low and for making little effort to integrate.
The increase in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why Singapore’s ruling party recorded its worst election result since independence last year.
After the elections, there was an effort to solve the problem through quotas and higher fees for foreign workers.
The Unexpected Consequences
While the decline in birth rates has known effects on national economic growth, tax revenues, health care spending, and immigration policy, there have also been some unexpected consequences in the case of Singapore.
The government is trying not to build so many small houses.
For example, it began to affect the real estate trade.
The Office for Urban Development began to regulate the number of small apartments known as "bot boxes" that can be built in certain urban areas.
These apartments have an area of 46 square meters and have had great success in sales.
However, there is a concern that these apartments can promote a youthful lifestyle and discourage developers from building large family houses.
But Lim Yew Soon, CEO of development firm EL Developers, claims that their “bot boxes” sell much faster than larger homes.
“They’re more popular because they sell days to weeks faster than larger houses.
That’s why they’re so much better for our cash flow.”
However, it admits that the new standards set clearer rules for developers who were previously limited when they wanted to offer too many small houses in one project.
Over-stressed
Singapore is a city-state.
While these new rules could aim to increase the nation’s birth rate, an interview with Singaporeans working in the city’s financial district suggests they won’t have much effect.
“People are still stressed, houses are expensive, as is education, which is why many people put it off,” the young official said.
"Let the others have children.
But it is important for me to rely on my own money and time,” says another, about 20-year-old, young man.
Both men and women cite career, stress, and the cost of living and education as reasons that prevent them from having children.
So no matter how the government tries to force citizens to have children, it is the Singaporeans who have the final say on starting a family.
What is private offline is private and online
Privacy.
According to the dictionary published by the Royal Spanish Academy, it is something that has a personal nature or “an area of private life that everyone has the right to protect against any disruption”.
What is privacy for a person under the age of 16?
How does he apply this definition in his daily life and on social networks?
Does he understand the dangers he is exposed to when he posts things on the Internet that he would certainly not tell anyone in normal communication?
Journalists from elPeri<0xC3><0xB3>dico interviewed five boys and girls between the ages of 10 and 15 who are frequent Internet users.
In four cases, they considered the concept of privacy to be "totally their own" on a personal level and "username and password" when it came to social networks.
“I wouldn’t reveal my biggest secret,” said Jorge, 10, in an effort to explain the importance of privacy in places like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had accounts for two years.
"They're very secret secrets, my mom might know about them, but not the whole world," he says.
"I put nice pictures or photos on FB as we play.
I also talk to friends there.
I wouldn’t share a photo that wasn’t mine, or a photo that made someone laugh,” she says.
This boy realizes that it is wrong to publish obscene photographs, photographs of naked persons or photographs of crimes, or to write humiliating or rude comments.
Jorge says he knows all 35 friends he has on FB and his nine Twitter followers.
Most of them are relatives.
Among them is a mother who has the name and password of one of the accounts.
“I set up a Twitter account to express my views and make interesting posts.
I don’t know if anyone will answer me, I just put them there,” he adds.
“Social networks are fun, I can talk to relatives who are far away or quickly communicate with friends,” he says.
Without hesitation, he says that he would never accept a request from an unknown person.
He wouldn't even care if someone recommended him to someone he didn't know.
The case of 14-year-old Jose is different.
The teenager has accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space, and Ask, and admits he doesn’t know 20 people on his friend list.
"I'm not afraid of it because we have something in common, like music," he says.
According to this boy, none of them were pointing him at anything, not even asking for his address or phone number.
“If they insist on me or demand that I do so, I will simply remove them from my account,” he admits.
Jose signed up for Ask after reading the recommendation on Twitter.
These guys are no strangers to the experience of what is now called cyberbullying.
"A friend of mine was blackmailed on social media.
They threatened him and demanded money.
“He never knew who it was,” he said.
According to Jose, the victim did not log out of the account.
"You just activated a private mode."
Then, it explains a series of steps on how to set up your account securely.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would post photos of acquaintances in uncomfortable or embarrassing situations.
"Of course I would if someone bothered me or if I just wanted to.
“I know it’s cyberbullying,” he said.
Key Questions
Marielos Porras, an English teacher and a graduate of Education and Teaching, believes that in order for children and adolescents to be properly oriented in social networks, they need to understand that the main goal of these networks is to inform.
“The Internet was created as a means of finding information, but when social networks appeared, the rules of the game changed.”
Marrielos Porras notes that academic Marc Prensky, a graduate of pedagogy at Yale University and author of Digital Natives and Digital Immigrants, introduced these terms to explain the phenomenon.
“Digital natives are children and young people who were born in the age of this technology.
We are digital immigrants who have to teach them, and yet we are still learning for ourselves,” he says.
He explains that this is a complex topic, "because we ask them to discern what is appropriate to disseminate, publish and say, and what is not, at an age when they are not yet ripe for it."
Also, to be – as far as the environment is concerned – prudent, at a time when what they most desire is to be popular, to have thousands of friends and not to think about the consequences,” he adds.
According to this specialist, the most effective way to show children and adolescents what privacy is is, asking questions that make them think.
“Telling them not to do something doesn’t work,” he adds.
Next, Marrielos Porras lists some of the options: There are things you wouldn’t tell a stranger, so why are you doing it on the Internet?
Or: Would you like someone to post your picture the way you posted your friend’s?
Do you know what others are posting about you?
When you tag people in photos from the celebrations, did you ask for their permission?
And one more thing: Does everyone need to know what you're doing all the time?
The next point is to realize that they must behave in the Internet environment as well as outside it.
They're the same rules.
“A person is governed by respect, morality and other principles outside the Internet, and the same should be on social networks,” he said.
Supervision
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, first-degree teacher and educational advisor, explains that it is essential that parents of children carefully read the rules of social networks.
“If they understand every little trick, they have a good reason to talk to their children about the consequences of setting up an account on the Internet.
For example, in terms of age or what is allowed to be shared or published,” he says.
Guardia is of the opinion that it is crucial to remind children of the traditional rule of "don't talk to strangers".
South American Summit Ends and Lima Statement Not Published
The sixth presidential summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) held in Peru today ended without issuing the Lima Declaration, which was announced and allegedly signed by the seven presidents present.
Efe has repeatedly tried to gain access to the document signed at the sixth meeting of the heads of state and government of Unasur, but representatives of the foreign ministry and the presidential office, who initially determined that the document will be published after the summit, said that it will later be published on the website of the Peruvian government.
They also said that the content was published by Peruvian President Ollanta Humala in several short press statements.
Journalists had limited access to information throughout the summit.
During the meeting, a video from the presidential assembly was broadcast in the press room without sound, with the message "confidential session, audio transmission prevented."
The small amount of information available to journalists was provided by the press spokespersons of some governments who were present, but not by Peruvian spokesmen.
The only document published during the meeting was a list of participating presidents, which caused the reluctance of hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who asked for more information.
Later, the Peruvian presidential office sent an e-mail to the media with a “final statement” from the summit, but this was only a statement by President Humala, and not an official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the third summit of the South American and Arab countries (América del Sur-Pa<0xC3><0xAD>ses Arabes, ASPA), and even on this occasion, the originally promised Declaration of Lima was not published, although the press was eagerly required.
On the official website of ASPA, it can be found that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities sought to ensure that the broadcast was broadcast to all journalists, but completely prevented the flow of information.
The summit ended, among other things, with a joint commitment by Chile and Peru to adopt the Hague Court’s judgment, which resolves the border dispute between the two countries.
Peru’s President Ollanta Humala and Chile’s President Sebastián Pi<0xC3><0xB1>era met during a regional meeting and confirmed that they would respect the decision of the International Court of Justice in The Hague, which on Monday will begin to discuss the dispute initiated by Lima against Santiago by hearing a defence speech by both sides.
"We will submit and execute a verdict that will resolve the dispute that we are discussing today in this international court," President Humala and his Chilean counterpart said.
"Chile has been, is and will be a country that respects international law, the peaceful settlement of disputes, conventions and international courts," Pi<0xC3><0xB1>era added, greeting President Humala with a handshake at the flags of both countries.
The two presidents' confirmation that they would submit to the International Court of Justice's decision was made public after Colombia adopted the Bogota Pact this week, thereby expressing submission to the judgments of the International Court of Justice, which ruled on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, and Colombia considered this decision to be completely wrong.
The summit was held without the participation of the presidents of Brazil (Dilma Rouseff), Venezuela (Hugo Chávez), Bolivia (Evo Morales) and Argentina (Cristina Kirchner).
Paraguay was expelled from Unasur in 2011 following the impeachment of then-President Fernando Lugo and did not attend the meeting.
Host President Ollanta Humala was tasked with opening the morning speeches and concluding the summit in Lima shortly after noon.
The president read the final document, in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and 31 projects between South American countries had been planned, with investments amounting to $17 billion.
In addition to the agreements adopted, he mentioned that UNASUR member states will take “important steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, which is why residence agreements are being extended”.
“We support actions to improve cooperation in the fight against civil uncertainty and international organized crime, to improve access to medicines and the low-cost Internet in all corners of South America, and to take joint and effective action against the risks of natural disasters.”
When Europe is in crisis, "economic consolidation [of Latin America] should not be about winning, but about expanding our productivity and showing our nations a better future," Humala added.
"We have decided to give priority to a group of 31 symbolic projects that will improve transport links between various places in South America, especially rural and border areas ... so that our countries are better connected and create new economic ties," the Peruvian president said in a read-out speech.
He mentioned that five of these projects relate to Peru and the transverse axes of its territory from the coast to Brazil, and the other two relate to a better connection with Ecuador, but he did not provide further details.
The final document also touched upon the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve to return it to the Union of South American Nations," from which it is currently excluded.
Another issue highlighted by the summit was the need for Latin America to remain a prosperous and peaceful region that is whole and has good neighbourly relations.
