Today’s AIDS victims are the result of a late diagnosis.
Fabrizi was 21 when his HIV-positive test was confirmed.
"It was as if lightning struck me," he says, recalling a moment of truth that the doctor had tried to "relief a little," but apparently without success.
The boy kept it a secret from his family.
He decided to take his illness on his own and began to inform himself about it with such commitment that he celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients of the HIV Unit at the Civil Hospital of Guadalajara (HCG), which he entered in 1994 after several bouts with the disease.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, something unimaginable in the early 1990s, when there was a lot of doubt, few treatment options, and more stigma.
At the time, even the director of the Mexican Social Security Institute (IMSS) clinic didn’t say goodbye to him, “because he had a cut.”
Back then, AIDS was synonymous with death.
Now it is possible to survive with this syndrome and live fully.
However, there are many people who do not know about their disease and come only when the virus has caused the destruction of the organism and amplified the immune system, and then become victims of accidental infections.
31 years since AIDS first emerged in the world, or at least since the first documented cases, "it is a great success that the life expectancy of a patient who begins treatment in a timely and appropriate manner is exactly the same as that of healthy people," said Jaime Andrade Villanueva, head of the HIV Unit at the Civil Hospital of Guadalajara in a press release.
Andrade Villanueva, an HIV/AIDS infectious disease specialist, explained that scientists have concluded that since 2008 AIDS is not a death sentence, but that the length of survival and a full life depends on the degree of disability of the immune system of patients diagnosed with the disease, better off than those who do not use drugs: people with 200 CD4 cells can live up to 500 years.
Simply put, this means that a person who is diagnosed with HIV at age 25 can, according to this knowledge, “live without problems up to 75 years while adhering to treatment,” the doctor explained in an interview.
To highlight this progress, it is worth recalling that the average life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years.
Although mortality has decreased significantly in recent years, and in the case of Mexico, the number of people who have died from AIDS has decreased from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (the yearbook of the Joint United Nations Programme on HIV/AIDS - UNAIDS), it is also true that 60 percent of patients have died since the discovery of AIDS, according to national statistics.
In the state of Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011 and 187 so far this May. However, universal access to antiretrovirals has been ensured since 2005.
Why do people continue to die from the effects of the disease?
"It seems to me that the problem is not in the access to treatment.
That's how I see it, that's how it happens in the hospital.
The problem is that patients come at a very advanced stage, because they do not know the state of the disease, that is, in the late stage of the disease."
He adds a persuasive figure: "Nine out of ten patients come when some associated infection has already manifested itself. The only thing to do in order to influence the overall mortality more is to diagnose the disease earlier, and therefore it is necessary to offer tests on a large scale to detect the disease to all persons who request them."
In his proposal, he agrees with specialists and officials from the State Council for the Prevention of AIDS in the state of Jalisco, as well as directly with patients like Fabrizio, who came to have tests done in a private laboratory just because his friend did it, and despite his young age, he had already developed AIDS and also suffered from Kaposi's sarcoma, a cancerous disease.
“Everything changes when you know you have AIDS.
Some think they're going to die, and they don't want to know anything else.
"If I'm going to die, I'd rather do it three times a week," they say, but that's not my case.
The change was for the better, I eat healthy, I exercise, I take medication.”
To this day, all his parents know is that he had cancer.
“I live a normal life like everyone else.
I work, I have a lot of activities, I travel, I lead an active sex life, but responsibly, I take care of myself and the other person,” says Fabrizio, who accepted the invitation to share his experience with the daily MILENIO JALISCO, to motivate those who are afraid with his testimony today as part of World AIDS Day.
"Let them get tested. If they risked it, let them know as soon as possible if they are HIV positive, it's better. And if they have been diagnosed, let them realize that they can live like anyone else if they are responsible."
This message summarizes the slogan of the battle against AIDS in 2012.
