There is a big gap between health programs and ordinary citizens, said Ricardo Salazar, a Guadalajara-based journalist who is seeking information on the HIV virus.
The biggest gaps are in prevention.
In places that are dedicated to this task, "there has indeed been an increase in the distribution of condoms, they used to give us one or two, today they give us packages and a hundred condoms, which is very good, but there are still people who do not have access to condoms," he said.
Among the most susceptible to new infections are adolescents.
“What do you want it for?” is a common question full of irony and judgment from social workers, school counselors, pharmacy staff, and medical staff who teens want to avoid, the reporter says.
He proposed to change this ineffective distribution, so that the condoms would not be just behind the counters, but in the dispensers in the public toilets, in places where young people often go.
“It’s not an endorsement of promiscuity.
Nor is it about “paying them for beer and a motel,” as Governor Emilio González responded when asked if he would agree to distributing condoms in his district.
It is best to make condoms available to those who already lead a sex life," he said.
