Thus, it seems that the procedures of restructuring companies, which are allowed by Mexican laws, in the country of stripes and stars, despite international agreements, do not apply.
The June 15 ruling by Judge Harlin Hale at the North Texas Bankruptcy Court leaves Mexican firms defenseless against the possibility of their assets being confiscated across the El Bravo River.
However, the ruling opens the door to the U.S. Supreme Court for the main Mexican glass producer with an appeal against three irregularities.
To begin with, while the judge of this case claims that creditors are to be governed by United States insolvency law, the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals, based in New Orleans, says that the main proceedings lay down bankruptcy proceedings in Mexico.
Firstly, it would point to the lack of knowledge of international procedural cooperation in cases of insolvency of multinational enterprises.
Essentially, the United Nations Model Law for the Unification of International Commercial Law was created for this purpose, which determines the organization of the American Law Institute as the arbiter.
Secondly, the judgment provides that without the vote of the branches of the internal corporate structure, when the debt of the parent company Vitro to the branches is recognised, the required majority for the approval of the restructuring would not have been achieved.
However, this possibility is allowed by Mexican law.
The fact is that the case of Vitro was not the first in which this scheme was adopted.
There are half a dozen examples, such as Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, whose intra-corporate debts were guaranteed by the Federal Bankruptcy Institute.
