Héctor "Hetin" Reyes: "Basketball was my life"
Héctor "Hetin" Reyes has been involved in this indoor sport for more than 60 years and has travelled the world thanks to it.
Few people in Puerto Rico have as many memories of the history of local basketball as Héctor "Hetin" Reyes.
Reyes was passionate about the sport for more than 60 years, whether as a junior player, a player of the national basketball league BSN, the owner and coach of the Vaqueros de Bayam<0xC3><0xB3>n team in the national basketball league, or the president of the Puerto Rican Basketball Federation.
“I’ve played a lot of roles in my life in basketball, including a few at the same time, like when I was president of the BSN National League in the 1990s, CEO of the national team, and chairman of the federation,” Reyes recalled during a visit to Primera Hora reporters at his home in Bayam<0xC3><0xB3>n, where he has lived for more than 50 years with his faithful husband, Isabel.
"Basketball was my life."
Reyes does not exaggerate in his claim.
The walls of his house, which are almost all decorated with photos and souvenirs from his long career, testify to this.
Bayam<0xC3><0xB3>n in the heart
With the greatest movement of all, he guards those that recall his time at Los Vaqueros from the mid-1950s, where he was a player until 1982, when he also celebrated 15 years as a co-owner or team owner.
"These were my best years, the ones I enjoyed the most, because I had the opportunity to participate with the Los Vaqueros team since 1967 in eight championships, whether as an owner, co-owner or coach.
It was a series of successful years, including five championships held between 1971 and 1975.
And then I said goodbye to one championship - in 1981, when Jerome Mincy made his debut at BSN.
Then the team took over "Cuco" Ortiz, who was an excellent leader," Reyes said.
“I remember Gene Bartow, who used to coach here and was at the University of Alabama at Birmingham at the time, said to me, ‘I have a two-meter tall player for you.
Do you want it? "
And that was the beginning of Mincy, one of the best players Puerto Rico has ever had.
Bartow then recommended the quarterback Raymond Gauss, who became a member of the team and one of our top scorers.
I remember he said that if Mincy brought Bayamona victory in the championship, Gauss would contribute to the next.
The championship, when los Vaqueros played for the team of Gauss, he enjoyed, but only remotely, because in 1988 he already held the post of president of the basketball federation.
At that time, he wanted to fully devote himself to his functions and enjoy Mincy’s position in the national team.
“I remember the first time we defeated the United States in the Olympic Qualifying Game in Mexico in 1989.
Then came the World Cup in 1990, where we finished fourth, but we should have had the bronze if it wasn’t for the Canadian referee who let us repeat the final line-up,” Reyes said.
Is the team from the 1990 World Cup the best national team you’ve ever seen?
He is among the best, as well as the one who defeated the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympics.
But my favorite was the national team at the 1991 Pan American Games in Cuba, when we won gold and beat the United States team, which was quite similar to the team that blew us bronze at the World Cup.
This team not only had Mincy, Gauss, Ramon Rivas, Fico L<0xC3><0xB3>pez, and "Picul<0xC3><0xAD>n" (Ortiz), but there were also young men (Javier) "To<0xC3><0xB1>ito" Col<0xC3><0xB3>n and James Carter, Leon brothers (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who could not be on the team in 1990 due to injury.
The team that may not have had the perfect composition, but managed to win us a gold medal and bring us great joy, was the team from the Olympic qualification in 1995 in Argentina's Neuquén.
With roster players such as "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and junior player Rolando Hourruitiner replacing players eliminated due to a skirmish at the Pan American Games in Mar de Plata, we won gold despite all predictions.
Who was the best player in Puerto Rico?
It was without a doubt Piculin Ortiz.
His numbers from international tournaments are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has achieved such results at this level as Picul<0xC3><0xAD>n.
Not to mention his work in various leagues where he played.
Who is the best Puerto Rican coach?
That's very difficult.
We had a very good generation, which includes Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau and Armandito Torres.
I love the work of Leo Arilla.
What do you consider to be your greatest achievement in the Federation?
That I was part of the most famous era of the national team from 1988 to 1995 and that in the early 1990s the national league BSN had up to 17 teams in one season.
What have you failed to prove?
There were things I wanted to introduce, like the division of youth categories by region.
For example, that the boys from Ponce would play only in their own area and compete with teams from other parts of the island only in national play-offs.
Now children travel a lot and play too many matches, which is not necessary.
I also see the benefit in mandatory certifications and courses for coaches, assistant referees and referees.
That's nice to meet you.
What do you do now?
I mostly listen to music, watch YouTube videos with music from my time, enjoy my grandchildren and sometimes go to basketball games.
And, of course, I enjoy the company of my wife, Isabel, who has always been by my side.
Actor Larry Hagman has died.
Larry Hagman, who was born on September 21, 1931 in Fort Worth, Texas, was world-famous for starring John Ross Ewing, better known as "J.R." in the Dallas television series, in which he portrayed a man who acted ruthlessly and was insidious and manipulative.
Larry Hagman, whose role as predatory oil tycoon J.R. Ewing in the Dallas television series became a symbol of poverty in the 1980s, has died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who returned as J.R. in the new Dallas series this year, died Friday afternoon of cancer-related complications, according to an official family statement provided to The Associated Press by the Dallas-based production company Warner Bros.
“Larry returned to his beloved hometown of Dallas, where he once again played the iconic role he loved most,” his family said in a statement.
Larry's family and his closest friends were in Dallas for Thanksgiving.
“Linda Gray, who represented his wife in both the original and new series, was with Hagman at the time of his death at the Dallas hospital,” her agent Jeffrey Lane said in a statement.
He brought joy to everyone he knew.
"He was creative, generous, funny, kind, kind and talented and I will miss him terribly.
He was unique and lived his life to the fullest," Gray said in a statement.
Hagman was diagnosed with cirrhosis of the liver in 1992, and he admitted to drinking heavily for years.
In 1995, a malignant tumor was found in his liver and Hagman underwent a transplant.
Years before the Dallas series aired, Hagman made a name for himself on television as a decent guy in NBC's light comedy I Dream of Jeannie from 1965 to 1970.
Here he played the character of Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life is changed when he meets an attractive girl (Gina), played by Barbara Eden, and takes her to his house to live together.
He also starred in two short-lived comedies, The Good Life (NBC, 1971-72) and Here We Go Again (ABC, 1973).
His acting in films included roles that were well received by critics: The Group, Harry and Tonto, and Primary Colors.
But it was Hangman’s mastery of the incredibly repulsive J.R. that led him to stardom.
A CBS drama series about the Ewing clan and other personalities around them aired from April 1978 to May 1991.
The propaganda slogan "Who Shot Jayar?", which was supposed to raise expectations for an emotional piece where Hangman's character is almost murdered, caused not only a huge number of spectator speculations around the world, but also millions of dollars in betting offices.
This also helped to set a record for this work.
The November 1980 episode, in which the answer was revealed, was watched by an average of 41 million television viewers, making Dallas the second-most-watched entertainment show in history after MASH in 1983, which was watched by 50 million viewers.
His sister-in-law Kristin (played by Mary Crosby) shot at J.R.
Kristin and J.R. got pregnant and he threatened to call her a prostitute if she didn't leave town, but there were others who had reason to attack him.
Hagman played Ewing, an insatiable greedy man with a charismatic smile: a deceitful businessman and an unfaithful husband who tried to have his alcoholic wife Sue Ellen (Linda Gray) locked up in a hospital.
"I know what I want J.R. to have on the headstone," Hagman said in 1988.
It should say, "Here lies the honorable citizen J.R. Ewing."
This is the only thing that didn't work out.
Victoria Principal, who played in the original series, recalled Hagman on Friday as someone who was "great on screen and off."
It is unforgettable and irreplaceable for millions of admirers in the world and in the hearts of all of us who have been lucky enough to know and love it.
Ten episodes of the new Dallas series aired on TNT a few months ago with great success.
"Five episodes of the second season have already been completed and the sixth was just being filmed," the network said in a statement.
Immediately after Hangman's death, there were no statements from Warner or TNT about how the series would continue.
A native of Fort Worth, Texas, he was the son of actress and singer Mary Martin, who starred in classics such as South Pacific and Peter Pan.
Mary Martin was a very young girl when she gave birth to Larry in 1931, whose father was her husband, lawyer Ben Hagman.
At the beginning of the 1950s, Larry tried his luck on the stage in New York, and then from 1952 to 1956 he served in the Air Force in England.
There he met a young Swedish designer, Maj Axelsson, whom he married.
The couple had two children, Preston and Heidi, and have lived for a long time in the Californian city of Malibu, where many celebrities reside.
In 2001, he published his autobiography Hello Darlin': Tall (and Absolutely True) Tales about My Life.
"I didn't put anything in there that I knew would hurt anyone or hurt them in any way," he told the Prensa Asociada news agency at the time.
After a liver transplant, he began to promote organ donation and worked as a volunteer in the hospital, where he helped fearful patients.
“I advise them, I give them courage, I meet them when they go into surgery and after,” he said in 1996.
I try to give them comfort in the sense of "do not worry, it will be a little uncomfortable for a while, but you will be healthy."
He was also an activist in the fight against smoking and participated in various campaigns.
Begins a course that explores "the end of the world"
Each week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria, and global warming.
When religion professor Stuart Charmé decided to take a course on the end of the world this semester, he knew it was an irresistible lure: The end of the "long count" of the Mayan calendar, due on December 21, caught many people as proof that the end of the world was coming.
Charmé, however, had no idea what lay ahead for him in the next few months: Hurricane Sandy, the budget chasm that some call “debt Armageddon,” and the growing conflict that Israel is drawn into, a place where, according to Christians theorizing about the end of the world, the Apocalypse will begin.
"I didn't realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester ever," Charmé told students at Rutgers University in Camden, New Jersey, this week.
When you look at what’s going on in the world today as if we have 30 days left, it’s a really good time.
And remember, bad means good for apocalyptic thinkers.
And it’s not the only professor offering courses on “the end of the world” this semester, which is theoretically the last in history.
Barry Vacker, an assistant professor at Temple University, is giving a course on “Means, Culture, and the End of the World.”
Each week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria, and global warming.
"We discuss why these ideas spread over time," he says, and how they offer hypothetical scenarios that govern certain human behavior.
If, for example, nuclear material falls into the hands of terrorists, war can break out.
This month, students analyze films with apocalyptic themes and examine how they differ from real-life examples.
“I tried to inform students about what is possible, likely, plausible and impossible,” Vacker says.
At the main campus of Pennsylvania State University, Latin American history professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of art history and anthropology, came together to organize a course simply called The End of the World.
“We don’t attach ‘2012’ because we always expect to be able to re-organise the course in case the world doesn’t end,” Restall said.
Despite the "threatening doom" students have to study, create projects and do final exams.
At Penn State, the final exam will take place on the eve of the Apocalypse, giving students no choice but to work “until the evening of the supposed end of the world,” Restall said.
The courses have become quite popular.
"It stretched out to two hours," Restall said of his course for high-average students, 35 of whom applied.
Weeks and weeks before the start of the semester, we received e-mails asking if there was still room.
The students themselves assure that the course is one of the most interesting.
“I find it fascinating to see what people do to comfort themselves,” said Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old religion and sociology student from Haddonfield, New Jersey, at Rutgers University in Camden.
Thus, apocalyptic, secular, or religious thinking is only a matter of comfort or lack thereof.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old psychology and nursing student, said he had seen all the apocalyptic movies.
"I've never heard of an hour where it could be taught," he said.
"I'm enjoying it."
But no student interviewed, let alone the professor, said he believed in the end date of December 21.
“Our first project dealt with Mayan predictions, and in a way we refute them,” said Julie Zeglen, a 21-year-old senior student at Temple University in West Chester.
"The Mayans never predicted the end of the world; it's just a key point in the calendar," Restall said.
But he added that in Western culture there is an apocalyptic anxiety that goes back several centuries, which people react to changes in their surroundings with predictions of the end of the world.
The rise of these speculations has been fueled by the Internet.
"Other people don't think about it," he said.
This is the case in the vast majority of the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at La Salle University, who is lecturing in the Philippines this year, responded quickly when asked if he knew of a course on the “end of the world.”
"The Philippines does not participate in the end of the world," he wrote, suggesting an exception at the highest office.
We have the grace of the Pope.
Restall noted that over the years, there has been talk of many days of final judgment, and said that if nothing happens on December 21, “people will immediately start thinking about the next date” or philosophizing that December 21 is the beginning of a seven-year period at the end of which the world will end.
The date is taken lightly by students and professors.
Several have said they intend to go to the "end of the world" celebration.
"I think I'll call a few friends and we'll laugh together," said Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
